{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T16:04:38.771860", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_claude/Nicotinamide-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_claude", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide: from spark discharge to complete NAD\u207a assembly\n\n**Nicotinamide\u2014the redox-active heterocycle at the heart of NAD\u207a\u2014can be assembled prebiotically through at least three independent routes from simple feedstocks, and has been detected in pristine asteroid samples.** The field has progressed from Orgel's foundational propiolaldehyde\u2013cyanoacetaldehyde condensation (1970) to Trapp's complete prebiotic NAD\u207a synthesis (2024), while meteoritic detections in Ryugu and Bennu confirm extraterrestrial vitamin B\u2083 formation as a robust cosmochemical process. Two principal pathways to the pyridine ring dominate the literature: (1) a Chichibabin-type cyclization from C\u2083 aldehyde precursors and ammonia, producing nicotinonitrile, and (2) a non-enzymatic recapitulation of the bacterial aspartate\u2013DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid. Both operate under prebiotically plausible conditions, but the glycosidic bond instability of nicotinamide riboside and the concentration problem remain fundamental bottlenecks.\n\n## Two convergent routes to the pyridine ring\n\nThe first prebiotic access to the nicotinamide heterocycle was demonstrated by Dowler, Fuller, Orgel, and Sanchez (*Science* 169, 1320\u20131321, 1970). Their route combines **propiolaldehyde** (HC\u2261C\u2013CHO, produced by electric discharge on CH\u2084/H\u2082O mixtures) with **cyanoacetaldehyde** (NCCH\u2082CHO, formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene) and ammonia. The two C\u2083 units condense to form **2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde**, a linear intermediate that undergoes Chichibabin-type ring closure with ammonia to yield **nicotinonitrile** (3-cyanopyridine). Stepwise hydrolysis then gives nicotinamide (partial) or nicotinic acid (complete). The 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde intermediate has proven to be a critical branch-point molecule: in the presence of ribosylamine (from ribose + ammonia), it cyclizes directly to nicotinonitrile riboside, coupling heterocycle formation with glycosylation in a single step.\n\nFriedmann, Miller, and Sanchez (*Science* 171, 1026\u20131027, 1971) complemented this work by showing that electric discharge on **ethylene + ammonia** generates pyridine and HCN, which recombine to produce all three cyanopyridine isomers\u2014nicotinonitrile (3-position), 2-cyanopyridine, and 4-cyanopyridine. The preferential formation of the 3-isomer under certain conditions partially addresses the regioselectivity question of why biology uses the 3-carboxamide rather than the 2- or 4-isomer, though selectivity remains incomplete. Miyakawa, Cleaves, and Miller (*PNAS* 99, 14628\u201314631, 2002) later demonstrated that even mildly reducing **CO\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082\u2013H\u2082O atmospheres**\u2014more geochemically plausible than strongly reducing CH\u2084-rich mixtures\u2014produce nicotinic acid alongside amino acids and nucleobases under electric discharge and proton irradiation.\n\nThe second major pathway mirrors the most ancient biosynthetic route to NAD\u207a. Cleaves and Miller (*J. Mol. Evol.* 52, 73\u201377, 2001) showed that the entire six-step bacterial de novo pathway from **aspartic acid + dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP)** proceeds non-enzymatically through **quinolinic acid** (pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid) to nicotinic acid. Yields reached **up to 7%**\u2014remarkably high for prebiotic chemistry. Phosphorylated substrates (DHAP, glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate) gave significantly higher yields than their non-phosphorylated analogs, suggesting catalytic roles for phosphate. When asparagine replaced aspartate, nicotinamide was produced directly. This result established that NAD biosynthesis could have originated as \"an inevitable consequence of life based on carbohydrates and amino acids,\" with enzymes added later to each step independently.\n\n## From nicotinamide to NAD\u207a: the complete prebiotic pathway\n\nThe assembly of the full NAD\u207a dinucleotide requires three additional transformations beyond heterocycle synthesis: N-glycosylation, phosphorylation, and pyrophosphate coupling. Each presents distinct prebiotic challenges.\n\n**Glycosylation.** Kim and Benner (*Chem. Eur. J.* 24, 581\u2013584, 2018) achieved the first prebiotically plausible ribosylation by reacting nicotinamide with **ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate** in the presence of Mg\u00b2\u207a or Ca\u00b2\u207a at **85\u00b0C** under evaporative conditions. The cyclic phosphate blocks the \u03b1-face of ribose, enforcing stereoselective \u03b2-glycoside formation. However, the product is the **2\u2032-phosphate regioisomer** rather than the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN. Critically, the same chemistry produces adenosine 2\u2032-phosphate, unifying RNA nucleotide and NAD\u207a precursor synthesis under shared conditions.\n\n**The Trapp group breakthrough.** Bechtel, Kurrle, and Trapp (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202402055, 2024) reported the **first complete prebiotic synthesis of NAD\u207a** from simple feedstocks. Their pathway proceeds through four stages: (1) cyanoacetaldehyde + propiolaldehyde form 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde; (2) this intermediate cyclizes with ribosylamine (pre-formed from ribose + ammonia) to yield **nicotinonitrile riboside**, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside; (3) **regioselective 5\u2032-phosphorylation** using ITO-P (isothiatriazine-3-one phosphate, formed under Strecker-type conditions with H\u2082S) at pH 6, 23\u00b0C over 7 days gives **NMN at ~2% yield**; (4) photochemical coupling of NMN with ITO-AMP (light-activated adenylate) under **278 nm UV irradiation** forms the pyrophosphate bond to yield NAD\u207a. A key procedural insight was that ammonia must be pre-mixed with ribose before addition of the aldehyde precursors; reversing the order produces only free nicotinonitrile without ribosylation. The photochemical activation step draws directly on Sutherland's methyl isocyanide phosphorimidazolide chemistry (Mariani, Russell, Javelle, and Sutherland, *JACS* 140, 8657\u20138661, 2018).\n\n## Connection to cyanosulfidic protometabolism\n\nNeither the Sutherland group (MRC LMB Cambridge) nor the Powner group (UCL) has published a paper directly targeting nicotinamide synthesis. However, the cyanosulfidic protometabolic network described in Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (*Nature Chemistry* 7, 301\u2013307, 2015) generates exactly the feedstocks required. **Cyanoacetylene** (HC\u2083N), produced from HCN + acetylene via Cu(I)-catalyzed Nieuwland-type coupling, hydrates in water to form cyanoacetaldehyde\u2014a direct substrate for pyridine ring formation. **Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde** emerge from HCN photoredox chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, *Nature Chemistry* 4, 895\u2013899, 2012), providing both the sugar precursor for ribosylation and the C\u2083 carbonyl for the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway. The cyanosulfidic conditions\u2014HCN, H\u2082S, Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, UV irradiation, phosphate buffering at ~pH 7, ~35\u00b0C\u2014are broadly compatible with nicotinamide ring closure, making cyanoacetaldehyde the critical nexus molecule connecting Sutherland-type chemistry to NAD\u207a assembly.\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence validates prebiotic synthesis\n\nNicotinic acid (niacin) is now established as an indigenous component of carbonaceous chondrites and pristine asteroid samples. Smith, Callahan, Gerakines, Dworkin, and House (*Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 136, 1\u201312, 2014) systematically surveyed eight Antarctic CM2 meteorites and detected nicotinic acid at **30\u2013600 ppb** in all samples, alongside picolinic acid, isonicotinic acid, and\u2014for the first time in meteorites\u2014pyridine dicarboxylic acids including quinolinic acid. Abundance **negatively correlated** with the degree of pre-terrestrial aqueous alteration, suggesting parent-body processing degrades these compounds. Pizzarello and Huang (2004, 2005) provided isotopic proof of extraterrestrial origin for Murchison nicotinic acid: **\u03b4D = +129\u2030 and \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C = +20\u2030**, values far outside terrestrial ranges.\n\nThe Hayabusa2 mission delivered the most compelling evidence. Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 14, 1292, 2023) detected nicotinic acid at **49\u201399 ppb** in pristine, hermetically sealed Ryugu samples\u2014more abundant than uracil (6\u201332 ppb). The OSIRIS-REx analysis of asteroid Bennu (Glavin et al., *Nature Astronomy*, 2025) found nicotinic acid alongside all five canonical nucleobases, 14 amino acids, and ~10,000 N-bearing molecular species, with N-heterocycle concentrations **5\u201310\u00d7 higher than Ryugu**.\n\n**Nicotinamide itself** (not just nicotinic acid) was first detected in meteorites by Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 13, 2008, 2022) using gentle room-temperature extraction and HPLC/ESI-HRMS on Murchison, Tagish Lake, and Murray samples. Previous studies missed nicotinamide because harsh acid hydrolysis conditions (6M HCl, 150\u00b0C) converted it entirely to nicotinic acid. This analytical insight resolved a long-standing gap and confirmed that both the amide and acid forms are present extraterrestrially. Isonicotinamide was co-detected, and the complete isomer suite (all positional isomers plus alkylated homologs) argues strongly against terrestrial contamination.\n\n## Interstellar ice chemistry as a formation mechanism\n\nSmith, Gerakines, and Callahan (*Chem. Commun.* 51, 11787\u201311790, 2015) demonstrated that proton irradiation of astrophysical ice analogs (H\u2082O:CO\u2082:pyridine = 100:20:1) produces nicotinic acid, quinolinic acid, and other pyridine carboxylic acids. In water-rich ices mimicking interstellar grain mantles, **nicotinic acid becomes the favored monocarboxylic acid isomer** (preferential 3-position carboxylation), and the product ratio (picolinic:isonicotinic:nicotinic \u2248 0.89:0.35:1.00) closely matches the least aqueously altered CM2 chondrites. This correspondence supports cosmic ray processing of N-heterocyclic ices as the primary formation mechanism, with subsequent parent-body aqueous alteration modifying the initial distribution.\n\nPaschek, Lee, Semenov, and Henning (*ChemPlusChem* 89, e202300508, 2024) modeled vitamin B\u2083 synthesis inside **carbonaceous planetesimals** using the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway: Strecker-derived aspartate + formose-derived glyceraldehyde/DHA at 0\u2013100\u00b0C, ~100 bar, in anaerobic aqueous solution. Their thermochemical equilibrium predictions match measured meteorite abundances, and the mechanism correctly predicts the absence of picolinic acid (consistent with observed meteorite data).\n\nNeither pyridine nor nicotinic acid has been definitively detected in the interstellar medium via radio/millimeter-wave spectroscopy, despite extensive searches. The non-detection is attributed to rapid photodestruction, chemical conversion, and dilution across many structural isomers. However, the 2018 detection of benzonitrile (McGuire et al., *Science*) and subsequent identifications of cyanonaphthalene isomers in TMC-1 confirm that six-membered aromatic rings are present in the ISM.\n\n## Environmental conditions and mineral catalysis\n\nThe three principal prebiotic environments each favor different steps in nicotinamide and NAD\u207a synthesis. **Volcanic/surficial settings** provide electric discharge (volcanic lightning) for generating HCN, cyanoacetylene, and propiolaldehyde, plus UV irradiation for the photochemical NAD\u207a coupling step. The Bechtel/Kurrle/Trapp pathway is most compatible with this environment. **Evaporitic/tidal settings** support Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation chemistry, which requires evaporative drying at 80\u201390\u00b0C with divalent metal ion catalysis, and borate minerals that stabilize ribose. **Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (serpentinizing systems) excel at NAD\u207a reduction: Henriques Pereira et al. (*Communications Chemistry* 8, 318, 2025) showed that Ni-Fe mineral surfaces reduce NAD\u207a specifically to **1,4-NADH** using H\u2082 gas at 40\u00b0C, pH 8.5, 5 bar H\u2082, while NMN lacking the AMP moiety is overreduced to biologically useless products. The AMP \"handle\" of NAD\u207a thus serves a functional prebiotic role\u2014protecting against overreduction on mineral surfaces\u2014suggesting the dinucleotide structure predates enzymes.\n\nMineral catalysts relevant to specific steps include:\n\n- **Ni-Fe alloys** (awaruite, taenite): Catalyze stereospecific NAD\u207a \u2192 1,4-NADH reduction with H\u2082; NiFe\u2083 nanopowder outperforms pure metals by ~300%\n- **Iron-sulfur minerals** (pyrite, pyrrhotite): Catalyze pyruvate and related \u03b1-keto acid transformations, generating aspartate precursors via reductive amination\n- **Phosphate minerals**: Catalytic role in Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway (phosphorylated substrates yield significantly more nicotinic acid)\n- **Borate minerals**: Stabilize ribose for glycosylation chemistry\n- **Cu(I)/Cu(II)**: Drive photoredox cycling in cyanosulfidic networks, generating cyanoacetylene and sugar precursors\n\n## Critical bottlenecks and unresolved challenges\n\n**The glycosidic bond problem** remains the most severe. The N-glycosidic bond in nicotinamide riboside is intrinsically labile because the positively charged pyridinium ring acts as an excellent leaving group. Free nicotinamide riboside hydrolyzes within hours at room temperature. Kim and Benner showed that 2\u2032-phosphorylation stabilizes the nucleoside, while Bechtel et al. required carefully controlled mild conditions (pH 6, 23\u00b0C) to preserve the bond during 5\u2032-phosphorylation. Whether nicotinamide riboside can persist long enough under realistic geological conditions for downstream chemistry\u2014or whether all steps must be telescoped into one-pot sequences\u2014is unresolved.\n\n**Regiochemistry** presents a dual challenge. Electric discharge produces all three cyanopyridine isomers, not exclusively the biologically relevant 3-isomer. And while the Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation produces the 2\u2032-phosphate (not the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN), the Trapp group's ITO-P achieves 5\u2032-selective phosphorylation at the cost of low yields (~2%). No prebiotic equivalent of the biological PRPP-mediated 5\u2032-ribosylation has been demonstrated.\n\n**The concentration problem** constrains multi-component condensation reactions. The Orgel/Chichibabin cyclization requires simultaneous presence of propiolaldehyde, cyanoacetaldehyde, and ammonia at concentrations sufficient for efficient ring closure. Evaporative concentration in ponds or tidal flats offers a solution but restricts viable geological settings. **The water problem**\u2014thermodynamic unfavorability of condensation reactions in dilute aqueous solution\u2014affects glycosylation, phosphoester, and pyrophosphate bond formation. Bechtel et al. overcome the pyrophosphate step with photochemical energy input, but this requires surficial UV access incompatible with deep-sea hydrothermal vent models.\n\nSebastianelli, Kaur, Chen, Krishnamurthy, and Mansy (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202400411, 2024) demonstrated that **free nicotinamide cannot accept electrons from pyruvate**\u2014only NMN and NAD\u207a support non-enzymatic redox cycling. The anomeric carbon (sugar attachment point) is essential for electron transfer. This places severe demands on prebiotic chemistry: the heterocycle alone is metabolically inert, and at minimum the complete nucleotide (NMN) must form before any useful redox chemistry can occur.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide has matured from isolated heterocycle formation to a complete, demonstrated pathway to NAD\u207a within five decades. The convergence of three independent lines of evidence\u2014laboratory synthesis, meteoritic detection, and astrophysical ice chemistry\u2014establishes nicotinic acid/nicotinamide as among the most prebiotically accessible cofactor precursors. The Orgel/Chichibabin route through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde and the Cleaves\u2013Miller biomimetic aspartate pathway represent genuinely distinct chemical strategies to the same heterocycle, operating under different but overlapping environmental conditions. The Trapp group's 2024 NAD\u207a synthesis marks a watershed, yet the field remains constrained by the fundamental tension between the lability of the nicotinamide glycosidic bond and the thermodynamic demands of building the full dinucleotide in water. The emerging functional evidence\u2014that the AMP handle protects against overreduction on mineral surfaces, and that free nicotinamide lacks redox activity\u2014reframes the problem: prebiotic chemistry must produce not merely the heterocycle, but the complete nucleotide, before NAD\u207a can participate in the protometabolic networks that origin-of-life models require. Whether this was achieved through one-pot telescoped sequences in geochemically structured environments, or through exogenous delivery of nicotinic acid followed by terrestrial ribosylation, remains the central open question.", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_claude/Nicotinamide-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_claude", "length": 16471}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
