O\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Nicotinamide\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Nicotinamide. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide: from spark discharge to complete NAD\u207a assembly\n\n**Nicotinamide\u2014the redox-active heterocycle at the heart of NAD\u207a\u2014can be assembled prebiotically through at least three independent routes from simple feedstocks, and has been detected in pristine asteroid samples.** The field has progressed from Orgel's foundational propiolaldehyde\u2013cyanoacetaldehyde condensation (1970) to Trapp's complete prebiotic NAD\u207a synthesis (2024), while meteoritic detections in Ryugu and Bennu confirm extraterrestrial vitamin B\u2083 formation as a robust cosmochemical process. Two principal pathways to the pyridine ring dominate the literature: (1) a Chichibabin-type cyclization from C\u2083 aldehyde precursors and ammonia, producing nicotinonitrile, and (2) a non-enzymatic recapitulation of the bacterial aspartate\u2013DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid. Both operate under prebiotically plausible conditions, but the glycosidic bond instability of nicotinamide riboside and the concentration problem remain fundamental bottlenecks.\n\n## Two convergent routes to the pyridine ring\n\nThe first prebiotic access to the nicotinamide heterocycle was demonstrated by Dowler, Fuller, Orgel, and Sanchez (*Science* 169, 1320\u20131321, 1970). Their route combines **propiolaldehyde** (HC\u2261C\u2013CHO, produced by electric discharge on CH\u2084/H\u2082O mixtures) with **cyanoacetaldehyde** (NCCH\u2082CHO, formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene) and ammonia. The two C\u2083 units condense to form **2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde**, a linear intermediate that undergoes Chichibabin-type ring closure with ammonia to yield **nicotinonitrile** (3-cyanopyridine). Stepwise hydrolysis then gives nicotinamide (partial) or nicotinic acid (complete). The 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde intermediate has proven to be a critical branch-point molecule: in the presence of ribosylamine (from ribose + ammonia), it cyclizes directly to nicotinonitrile riboside, coupling heterocycle formation with glycosylation in a single step.\n\nFriedmann, Miller, and Sanchez (*Science* 171, 1026\u20131027, 1971) complemented this work by showing that electric discharge on **ethylene + ammonia** generates pyridine and HCN, which recombine to produce all three cyanopyridine isomers\u2014nicotinonitrile (3-position), 2-cyanopyridine, and 4-cyanopyridine. The preferential formation of the 3-isomer under certain conditions partially addresses the regioselectivity question of why biology uses the 3-carboxamide rather than the 2- or 4-isomer, though selectivity remains incomplete. Miyakawa, Cleaves, and Miller (*PNAS* 99, 14628\u201314631, 2002) later demonstrated that even mildly reducing **CO\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082\u2013H\u2082O atmospheres**\u2014more geochemically plausible than strongly reducing CH\u2084-rich mixtures\u2014produce nicotinic acid alongside amino acids and nucleobases under electric discharge and proton irradiation.\n\nThe second major pathway mirrors the most ancient biosynthetic route to NAD\u207a. Cleaves and Miller (*J. Mol. Evol.* 52, 73\u201377, 2001) showed that the entire six-step bacterial de novo pathway from **aspartic acid + dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP)** proceeds non-enzymatically through **quinolinic acid** (pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid) to nicotinic acid. Yields reached **up to 7%**\u2014remarkably high for prebiotic chemistry. Phosphorylated substrates (DHAP, glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate) gave significantly higher yields than their non-phosphorylated analogs, suggesting catalytic roles for phosphate. When asparagine replaced aspartate, nicotinamide was produced directly. This result established that NAD biosynthesis could have originated as \"an inevitable consequence of life based on carbohydrates and amino acids,\" with enzymes added later to each step independently.\n\n## From nicotinamide to NAD\u207a: the complete prebiotic pathway\n\nThe assembly of the full NAD\u207a dinucleotide requires three additional transformations beyond heterocycle synthesis: N-glycosylation, phosphorylation, and pyrophosphate coupling. Each presents distinct prebiotic challenges.\n\n**Glycosylation.** Kim and Benner (*Chem. Eur. J.* 24, 581\u2013584, 2018) achieved the first prebiotically plausible ribosylation by reacting nicotinamide with **ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate** in the presence of Mg\u00b2\u207a or Ca\u00b2\u207a at **85\u00b0C** under evaporative conditions. The cyclic phosphate blocks the \u03b1-face of ribose, enforcing stereoselective \u03b2-glycoside formation. However, the product is the **2\u2032-phosphate regioisomer** rather than the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN. Critically, the same chemistry produces adenosine 2\u2032-phosphate, unifying RNA nucleotide and NAD\u207a precursor synthesis under shared conditions.\n\n**The Trapp group breakthrough.** Bechtel, Kurrle, and Trapp (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202402055, 2024) reported the **first complete prebiotic synthesis of NAD\u207a** from simple feedstocks. Their pathway proceeds through four stages: (1) cyanoacetaldehyde + propiolaldehyde form 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde; (2) this intermediate cyclizes with ribosylamine (pre-formed from ribose + ammonia) to yield **nicotinonitrile riboside**, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside; (3) **regioselective 5\u2032-phosphorylation** using ITO-P (isothiatriazine-3-one phosphate, formed under Strecker-type conditions with H\u2082S) at pH 6, 23\u00b0C over 7 days gives **NMN at ~2% yield**; (4) photochemical coupling of NMN with ITO-AMP (light-activated adenylate) under **278 nm UV irradiation** forms the pyrophosphate bond to yield NAD\u207a. A key procedural insight was that ammonia must be pre-mixed with ribose before addition of the aldehyde precursors; reversing the order produces only free nicotinonitrile without ribosylation. The photochemical activation step draws directly on Sutherland's methyl isocyanide phosphorimidazolide chemistry (Mariani, Russell, Javelle, and Sutherland, *JACS* 140, 8657\u20138661, 2018).\n\n## Connection to cyanosulfidic protometabolism\n\nNeither the Sutherland group (MRC LMB Cambridge) nor the Powner group (UCL) has published a paper directly targeting nicotinamide synthesis. However, the cyanosulfidic protometabolic network described in Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (*Nature Chemistry* 7, 301\u2013307, 2015) generates exactly the feedstocks required. **Cyanoacetylene** (HC\u2083N), produced from HCN + acetylene via Cu(I)-catalyzed Nieuwland-type coupling, hydrates in water to form cyanoacetaldehyde\u2014a direct substrate for pyridine ring formation. **Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde** emerge from HCN photoredox chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, *Nature Chemistry* 4, 895\u2013899, 2012), providing both the sugar precursor for ribosylation and the C\u2083 carbonyl for the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway. The cyanosulfidic conditions\u2014HCN, H\u2082S, Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, UV irradiation, phosphate buffering at ~pH 7, ~35\u00b0C\u2014are broadly compatible with nicotinamide ring closure, making cyanoacetaldehyde the critical nexus molecule connecting Sutherland-type chemistry to NAD\u207a assembly.\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence validates prebiotic synthesis\n\nNicotinic acid (niacin) is now established as an indigenous component of carbonaceous chondrites and pristine asteroid samples. Smith, Callahan, Gerakines, Dworkin, and House (*Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 136, 1\u201312, 2014) systematically surveyed eight Antarctic CM2 meteorites and detected nicotinic acid at **30\u2013600 ppb** in all samples, alongside picolinic acid, isonicotinic acid, and\u2014for the first time in meteorites\u2014pyridine dicarboxylic acids including quinolinic acid. Abundance **negatively correlated** with the degree of pre-terrestrial aqueous alteration, suggesting parent-body processing degrades these compounds. Pizzarello and Huang (2004, 2005) provided isotopic proof of extraterrestrial origin for Murchison nicotinic acid: **\u03b4D = +129\u2030 and \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C = +20\u2030**, values far outside terrestrial ranges.\n\nThe Hayabusa2 mission delivered the most compelling evidence. Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 14, 1292, 2023) detected nicotinic acid at **49\u201399 ppb** in pristine, hermetically sealed Ryugu samples\u2014more abundant than uracil (6\u201332 ppb). The OSIRIS-REx analysis of asteroid Bennu (Glavin et al., *Nature Astronomy*, 2025) found nicotinic acid alongside all five canonical nucleobases, 14 amino acids, and ~10,000 N-bearing molecular species, with N-heterocycle concentrations **5\u201310\u00d7 higher than Ryugu**.\n\n**Nicotinamide itself** (not just nicotinic acid) was first detected in meteorites by Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 13, 2008, 2022) using gentle room-temperature extraction and HPLC/ESI-HRMS on Murchison, Tagish Lake, and Murray samples. Previous studies missed nicotinamide because harsh acid hydrolysis conditions (6M HCl, 150\u00b0C) converted it entirely to nicotinic acid. This analytical insight resolved a long-standing gap and confirmed that both the amide and acid forms are present extraterrestrially. Isonicotinamide was co-detected, and the complete isomer suite (all positional isomers plus alkylated homologs) argues strongly against terrestrial contamination.\n\n## Interstellar ice chemistry as a formation mechanism\n\nSmith, Gerakines, and Callahan (*Chem. Commun.* 51, 11787\u201311790, 2015) demonstrated that proton irradiation of astrophysical ice analogs (H\u2082O:CO\u2082:pyridine = 100:20:1) produces nicotinic acid, quinolinic acid, and other pyridine carboxylic acids. In water-rich ices mimicking interstellar grain mantles, **nicotinic acid becomes the favored monocarboxylic acid isomer** (preferential 3-position carboxylation), and the product ratio (picolinic:isonicotinic:nicotinic \u2248 0.89:0.35:1.00) closely matches the least aqueously altered CM2 chondrites. This correspondence supports cosmic ray processing of N-heterocyclic ices as the primary formation mechanism, with subsequent parent-body aqueous alteration modifying the initial distribution.\n\nPaschek, Lee, Semenov, and Henning (*ChemPlusChem* 89, e202300508, 2024) modeled vitamin B\u2083 synthesis inside **carbonaceous planetesimals** using the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway: Strecker-derived aspartate + formose-derived glyceraldehyde/DHA at 0\u2013100\u00b0C, ~100 bar, in anaerobic aqueous solution. Their thermochemical equilibrium predictions match measured meteorite abundances, and the mechanism correctly predicts the absence of picolinic acid (consistent with observed meteorite data).\n\nNeither pyridine nor nicotinic acid has been definitively detected in the interstellar medium via radio/millimeter-wave spectroscopy, despite extensive searches. The non-detection is attributed to rapid photodestruction, chemical conversion, and dilution across many structural isomers. However, the 2018 detection of benzonitrile (McGuire et al., *Science*) and subsequent identifications of cyanonaphthalene isomers in TMC-1 confirm that six-membered aromatic rings are present in the ISM.\n\n## Environmental conditions and mineral catalysis\n\nThe three principal prebiotic environments each favor different steps in nicotinamide and NAD\u207a synthesis. **Volcanic/surficial settings** provide electric discharge (volcanic lightning) for generating HCN, cyanoacetylene, and propiolaldehyde, plus UV irradiation for the photochemical NAD\u207a coupling step. The Bechtel/Kurrle/Trapp pathway is most compatible with this environment. **Evaporitic/tidal settings** support Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation chemistry, which requires evaporative drying at 80\u201390\u00b0C with divalent metal ion catalysis, and borate minerals that stabilize ribose. **Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (serpentinizing systems) excel at NAD\u207a reduction: Henriques Pereira et al. (*Communications Chemistry* 8, 318, 2025) showed that Ni-Fe mineral surfaces reduce NAD\u207a specifically to **1,4-NADH** using H\u2082 gas at 40\u00b0C, pH 8.5, 5 bar H\u2082, while NMN lacking the AMP moiety is overreduced to biologically useless products. The AMP \"handle\" of NAD\u207a thus serves a functional prebiotic role\u2014protecting against overreduction on mineral surfaces\u2014suggesting the dinucleotide structure predates enzymes.\n\nMineral catalysts relevant to specific steps include:\n\n- **Ni-Fe alloys** (awaruite, taenite): Catalyze stereospecific NAD\u207a \u2192 1,4-NADH reduction with H\u2082; NiFe\u2083 nanopowder outperforms pure metals by ~300%\n- **Iron-sulfur minerals** (pyrite, pyrrhotite): Catalyze pyruvate and related \u03b1-keto acid transformations, generating aspartate precursors via reductive amination\n- **Phosphate minerals**: Catalytic role in Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway (phosphorylated substrates yield significantly more nicotinic acid)\n- **Borate minerals**: Stabilize ribose for glycosylation chemistry\n- **Cu(I)/Cu(II)**: Drive photoredox cycling in cyanosulfidic networks, generating cyanoacetylene and sugar precursors\n\n## Critical bottlenecks and unresolved challenges\n\n**The glycosidic bond problem** remains the most severe. The N-glycosidic bond in nicotinamide riboside is intrinsically labile because the positively charged pyridinium ring acts as an excellent leaving group. Free nicotinamide riboside hydrolyzes within hours at room temperature. Kim and Benner showed that 2\u2032-phosphorylation stabilizes the nucleoside, while Bechtel et al. required carefully controlled mild conditions (pH 6, 23\u00b0C) to preserve the bond during 5\u2032-phosphorylation. Whether nicotinamide riboside can persist long enough under realistic geological conditions for downstream chemistry\u2014or whether all steps must be telescoped into one-pot sequences\u2014is unresolved.\n\n**Regiochemistry** presents a dual challenge. Electric discharge produces all three cyanopyridine isomers, not exclusively the biologically relevant 3-isomer. And while the Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation produces the 2\u2032-phosphate (not the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN), the Trapp group's ITO-P achieves 5\u2032-selective phosphorylation at the cost of low yields (~2%). No prebiotic equivalent of the biological PRPP-mediated 5\u2032-ribosylation has been demonstrated.\n\n**The concentration problem** constrains multi-component condensation reactions. The Orgel/Chichibabin cyclization requires simultaneous presence of propiolaldehyde, cyanoacetaldehyde, and ammonia at concentrations sufficient for efficient ring closure. Evaporative concentration in ponds or tidal flats offers a solution but restricts viable geological settings. **The water problem**\u2014thermodynamic unfavorability of condensation reactions in dilute aqueous solution\u2014affects glycosylation, phosphoester, and pyrophosphate bond formation. Bechtel et al. overcome the pyrophosphate step with photochemical energy input, but this requires surficial UV access incompatible with deep-sea hydrothermal vent models.\n\nSebastianelli, Kaur, Chen, Krishnamurthy, and Mansy (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202400411, 2024) demonstrated that **free nicotinamide cannot accept electrons from pyruvate**\u2014only NMN and NAD\u207a support non-enzymatic redox cycling. The anomeric carbon (sugar attachment point) is essential for electron transfer. This places severe demands on prebiotic chemistry: the heterocycle alone is metabolically inert, and at minimum the complete nucleotide (NMN) must form before any useful redox chemistry can occur.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide has matured from isolated heterocycle formation to a complete, demonstrated pathway to NAD\u207a within five decades. The convergence of three independent lines of evidence\u2014laboratory synthesis, meteoritic detection, and astrophysical ice chemistry\u2014establishes nicotinic acid/nicotinamide as among the most prebiotically accessible cofactor precursors. The Orgel/Chichibabin route through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde and the Cleaves\u2013Miller biomimetic aspartate pathway represent genuinely distinct chemical strategies to the same heterocycle, operating under different but overlapping environmental conditions. The Trapp group's 2024 NAD\u207a synthesis marks a watershed, yet the field remains constrained by the fundamental tension between the lability of the nicotinamide glycosidic bond and the thermodynamic demands of building the full dinucleotide in water. The emerging functional evidence\u2014that the AMP handle protects against overreduction on mineral surfaces, and that free nicotinamide lacks redox activity\u2014reframes the problem: prebiotic chemistry must produce not merely the heterocycle, but the complete nucleotide, before NAD\u207a can participate in the protometabolic networks that origin-of-life models require. Whether this was achieved through one-pot telescoped sequences in geochemically structured environments, or through exogenous delivery of nicotinic acid followed by terrestrial ribosylation, remains the central open question.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Nicotinamide\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network uses literature-grounded convergent prebiotic routes to nicotinamide centered on two experimentally supported heterocycle-forming strategies: (1) the Orgel/Trapp C3+C3 condensation route through cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, and 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile, nicotinamide, and nicotinamide riboside; and (2) the Cleaves-Miller biomimetic aspartate + DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid and nicotinamide. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, pyruvate, and aspartate precursors; surface cyanosulfidic and evaporitic chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, ribose/ribosylamine, and phosphorylation capacity; biochemical/prebiotic steps complete amidation/hydrolysis and glycosylation-linked access to nicotinamide. Ten distinct pathways to nicotinamide are traced through shared hub molecules: cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, nicotinonitrile, quinolinic acid, and nicotinic acid.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-3(4(8)9)1-2(6)7/h3H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"serine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7O6P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-3(5)2-9-10(6,7)8/h1,3-5H,2H2,(H2,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7O6P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroxyacetone phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-2(5)3-9-10(6,7)8/h4-5H,1,3H2,(H2,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3HN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-ynenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanoacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-oxopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-ynal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"propiolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H2O/c1-2-3-4/h1,3H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H4NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-cyanohexa-2,4-dienedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-3-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H4N2/c7-5-6-2-1-3-8-4-6/h1-4H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-3-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H5NO2/c8-6(9)5-2-1-3-7-4-5/h1-4H,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-3-carboxamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H6N2O/c7-6(9)5-2-1-3-8-4-5/h1-4H,(H2,7,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H14O7\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pentose\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11-1/h2-10H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ribosylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribosylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H11N3O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoylpyridinium riboside\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide riboside\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H5NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"quinolinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C7H5NO4/c9-6(10)4-2-1-3-8-5(4)7(11)12/h1-3H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H7NO8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoyl-1-beta-D-ribofuranosylpyridinium 5-phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide mononucleotide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde-equivalent reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation furnishes reduced C1 carbonyl products that can feed formose-type homologation chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-bearing minerals are documented to reduce CO2 to small reduced organics under alkaline vent conditions, providing prebiotic carbonyl feedstocks for downstream sugar chemistry; used here as a literature-consistent connector into surface formose/cyanosulfidic networks rather than as a nicotinamide-specific step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sugar homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic pools; borate stabilizes sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-like aldehyde homologation and photoredox sugar generation produce C2 and C3 sugars, with borate stabilization of product pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are established products of prebiotic photoredox/formose-related chemistry and are explicitly identified in cyanosulfidic protometabolism as feedstocks linked to nicotinamide synthesis; borate mineral stabilization is supported for ribose/sugar preservation (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of aspartate precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent chemistry with reductive amination and alpha-keto acid interconversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-sulfur-catalyzed reductive amination/transamination networks generate amino acid pools including serine and aspartate precursors from hydrothermal carbon fixation products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research notes iron-sulfur minerals as catalysts for pyruvate and related alpha-keto acid transformations generating aspartate precursors via reductive amination; aspartate is required for the Cleaves-Miller route, so this reaction connects hydrothermal metabolism-like chemistry to the biomimetic NAD pathway (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019; Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphorylation and isomerization of glyceraldehyde to triose phosphates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate-buffered evaporitic settings with wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated phosphorylation of C3 sugars followed by keto-enol isomerization yields glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller found phosphorylated substrates such as DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate give markedly higher yields in the non-enzymatic NAD de novo pathway; phosphate therefore has a catalytic and substrate-defining role in the network (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral-supported Cu(I)/Cu(II)-type photoredox proxy system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered near pH 7, cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox cyanation/coupling chemistry generates cyanoacetylene as a key nitrile feedstock for cyanoacetaldehyde production.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly identifies cyanoacetylene as a cyanosulfidic product linking Sutherland chemistry to nicotinamide synthesis, formed from HCN and acetylene under Cu(I)-driven conditions; mineral sulfides are included to satisfy the required surface mineral specification while keeping the chemistry aligned with the reported cyanosulfidic framework (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces assisting aqueous hydration and concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow aqueous pools, UV-exposed\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aqueous hydration of cyanoacetylene furnishes cyanoacetaldehyde, the critical nexus molecule for pyridine-ring construction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde formation by hydration of cyanoacetylene is directly described in the literature summary and is central to both Orgel-type nicotinonitrile synthesis and Trapp's NAD pathway; this molecule is the key nexus connecting cyanosulfidic chemistry to nicotinamide assembly (Dowler et al., 1970; Patel et al., 2015; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Electric-discharge generation of propiolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces in spark-discharge volcanic setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"electric discharge on CH4/H2O or related volcanic atmospheric mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy discharge chemistry furnishes propiolaldehyde as the second C3 carbonyl partner for Chichibabin-type pyridine synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Propiolaldehyde was specifically reported as a discharge product and one of the two essential C3 precursors for the Dowler-Orgel-Sanchez route and the Trapp sequence; this is one of the best-supported entry points into nicotinamide ring formation (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative concentration; anoxic ammonia-compatible conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C3+C3 condensation gives the linear conjugated dialdehyde nitrile intermediate that branches toward nicotinonitrile or ribosylated nicotinonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"2-Cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde is the critical branch-point intermediate identified by Orgel and later used by Trapp for direct coupling to ribosylamine. Its formation from cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde is central to the literature-grounded network (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Chichibabin-type cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ammonia to nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic/tidal concentration with NH3 present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-promoted ring closure/aromatization of the dialdehyde nitrile forms pyridine-3-carbonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the defining Orgel/Dowler step for prebiotic access to the nicotinamide heterocycle precursor and remains one of the two principal experimentally demonstrated routes to the biologically relevant 3-substituted pyridine ring (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Stepwise hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide and nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise aqueous hydrolysis; partial hydrolysis stops at amide, complete hydrolysis reaches acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration gives the amide, and further hydrolysis yields the carboxylic acid; both products are reachable from the nitrile under aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. explicitly reported stepwise hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide and nicotinic acid. This reaction creates one major convergence point: both heterocycle-first routes and riboside-first routes can feed the same nicotinamide/nicotinic acid product pool (Dowler et al., 1970; Oba et al., 2022 for nicotinamide occurrence).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose formation and stabilization in evaporitic surface settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"formose-like sugar network in borate-bearing geothermal fields\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C2/C3 sugars feed borate-stabilized pentose production, furnishing ribose for ribosylamine and nucleoside formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research specifically notes glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors for ribosylation and borate minerals as stabilizers of ribose under prebiotic conditions relevant to nicotinamide chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonolysis of ribose to ribosylamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild warming\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-stabilized evaporitic chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia premixed with ribose before aldehyde addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of ammonia with ribose gives ribosylamine, the glycosyl donor used directly in pyridine-ring-forming cyclization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. showed that ribosylamine must be pre-formed by mixing ribose and ammonia before aldehyde precursors are added; otherwise only free nicotinonitrile forms. This procedural order is essential in the literature and is preserved here (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ribosylamine to nicotinamide riboside precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild, near ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"evaporative mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia premixed with ribose; one-pot coupling/heterocyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The branch-point dialdehyde reacts with ribosylamine to form nicotinonitrile riboside, which hydrolyzes within the same reaction network to nicotinamide riboside.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core Trapp-group innovation: coupling heterocycle formation and glycosylation in a single step through the 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde branch point, bypassing separate unstable nicotinamide ribosylation. The output is represented as the hydrolyzed nicotinamide riboside pool for network compactness (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ITO-P phosphorylation system with phosphate-rich setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 6, 7 days, regioselective 5'-phosphorylation, low yield (~2%)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated phosphate transfer to the riboside gives nicotinamide mononucleotide while preserving the labile N-glycosidic bond under mild acidic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. reported regioselective 5'-phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside using ITO-P at pH 6 and 23C over 7 days to yield NMN. This step addresses the key glycosidic-bond bottleneck and is included exactly because the literature identifies it as the route to a stable redox-active nicotinamide nucleotide intermediate (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic cleavage of nicotinamide riboside or NMN to nicotinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reflects glycosidic bond lability of nicotinamide riboside under aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Labile N-glycosidic bond hydrolysis liberates free nicotinamide from ribosylated nicotinamide derivatives.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research highlights the intrinsic lability of nicotinamide riboside, which hydrolyzes within hours at room temperature, and notes stabilization upon phosphorylation. This provides a literature-supported route from ribosylated intermediates back to free nicotinamide (Kim & Benner, 2018; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biomimetic non-enzymatic assembly of quinolinic acid from aspartate and DHAP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable aqueous prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate-rich substrates enhance yield; non-enzymatic six-step analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aspartate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate undergo a sequence analogous to the bacterial de novo NAD pathway, converging on quinolinic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller demonstrated that the entire bacterial de novo route from aspartate + DHAP proceeds non-enzymatically to quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, with yields up to 7%, making this one of the strongest literature-grounded alternative routes to the nicotinamide scaffold (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable aqueous prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"continuation of non-enzymatic de novo NAD sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Decarboxylative/rearrangement steps within the biomimetic NAD pathway convert quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Quinolinic acid is explicitly the key heterocyclic intermediate in the Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic pathway, and nicotinic acid is the documented downstream product. Meteorite detection of both compounds also supports their prebiotic relevance (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Asparagine-analog direct route to nicotinamide from amino acid + triose phosphate chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable aqueous prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"biomimetic variant of the Cleaves-Miller pathway representing direct amide-forming branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"An amidated amino-acid/triose-phosphate pathway analogous to the asparagine substitution experiment yields the amide product directly without requiring nicotinic acid hydrolysis/amidation sequencing.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller reported that when asparagine replaced aspartate, nicotinamide was produced directly. Because asparagine itself is not separately defined in this compact network, serine/aspartate-amide precursor chemistry is used as the minimal connector while retaining the literature-grounded conclusion that an amidated amino-acid entry can lead directly to nicotinamide. This is the one intentionally compacted representation in the network and is therefore mildly schematic but literature-based (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Aqueous amidation equilibrium between nicotinic acid and nicotinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild heating to ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"amide/acid interconversion represented as a connecting step to complete the nicotinamide pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carboxyl activation/ammonolysis under prebiotic aqueous cycling is represented as a network-level conversion from nicotinic acid to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature clearly establishes both nicotinic acid and nicotinamide as members of the same prebiotic product family in laboratory and meteoritic settings; while direct prebiotic amidation conditions are less explicitly detailed than nitrile hydrolysis, this connector is necessary to unify the acid-producing Cleaves-Miller branch with the target nicotinamide pool and is therefore marked as a conservative network-completion step consistent with the observed co-occurrence of both compounds (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Oba et al., 2022; Oba et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydration to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV photochemistry in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration/photochemical conversion of HCN furnishes formamide, a general amidation/nitrogen-transfer reagent in prebiotic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN to formamide photochemistry is part of the broader surface prebiotic chemistry framework summarized in the instructions, and including formamide provides a literature-compatible amide donor pool that helps connect nitrile, acid, and amide nodes without contradicting nicotinamide-specific findings (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Orgel direct nicotinonitrile hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene-derived cyanoacetaldehyde condenses with discharge-derived propiolaldehyde; the resulting branch-point dialdehyde cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile, which partially hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-carbon-fed Orgel route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface sugar chemistry and atmospheric/cyanosulfidic feedstocks, converging on the same Orgel nicotinonitrile branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Trapp ribosylamine-coupled route with hydrolytic release\",\n      \"description\": \"The Orgel dialdehyde reacts with preformed ribosylamine to create nicotinamide riboside, whose labile glycosidic bond hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Trapp NMN branch with downstream cleavage to nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Ribosylamine-coupled heterocycle formation is followed by 5'-phosphorylation to NMN; subsequent hydrolytic breakdown returns free nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cleaves-Miller de novo pathway via quinolinic acid\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal amino-acid generation and surface phosphorylation provide aspartate and DHAP for the non-enzymatic bacterial-like pathway through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid and then nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cleaves-Miller direct amide branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A biomimetic amidated amino-acid branch analogous to the asparagine substitution experiment furnishes nicotinamide directly from amino acid and DHAP chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Quinolinic-acid-first variant seeded by hydrothermal carbon\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon to sugar chemistry, which then enters triose phosphate formation and the quinolinic acid pathway to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose-assisted surface route converging back through nicotinonitrile hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface sugar chemistry generates ribose and ribosylamine, but if ribosylation is incomplete the same dialdehyde pool can instead cyclize with ammonia to nicotinonitrile and hydrolyze to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Nicotinic-acid reservoir to nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Any route generating nicotinic acid, including Cleaves-Miller or nitrile overhydrolysis, can feed a shared nicotinic-acid reservoir that converts to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteorite-compatible mixed network route\",\n      \"description\": \"This mixed pathway reflects the co-occurrence of quinolinic acid, nicotinic acid, and nicotinamide in extraterrestrial samples by combining the biomimetic quinolinate branch with amide-forming equilibration into the target pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_018\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Nicotinamide", "overall_strategy": "The network uses literature-grounded convergent prebiotic routes to nicotinamide centered on two experimentally supported heterocycle-forming strategies: (1) the Orgel/Trapp C3+C3 condensation route through cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, and 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile, nicotinamide, and nicotinamide riboside; and (2) the Cleaves-Miller biomimetic aspartate + DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid and nicotinamide. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, pyruvate, and aspartate precursors; surface cyanosulfidic and evaporitic chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, ribose/ribosylamine, and phosphorylation capacity; biochemical/prebiotic steps complete amidation/hydrolysis and glycosylation-linked access to nicotinamide. Ten distinct pathways to nicotinamide are traced through shared hub molecules: cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, nicotinonitrile, quinolinic acid, and nicotinic acid.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-3(4(8)9)1-2(6)7/h3H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H7NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxypropanoic acid", "common_name": "serine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO3/c4-2(3(6)7)1-5/h2,5H,1,4H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C3H7O6P", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal phosphate", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-3(5)2-9-10(6,7)8/h1,3-5H,2H2,(H2,6,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H7O6P", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one phosphate", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-2(5)3-9-10(6,7)8/h4-5H,1,3H2,(H2,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3HN", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H2O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynal", "common_name": "propiolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H2O/c1-2-3-4/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H4NO2", "iupac_name": "2-cyanohexa-2,4-dienedial", "common_name": "2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H4N2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carbonitrile", "common_name": "nicotinonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H4N2/c7-5-6-2-1-3-8-4-6/h1-4H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C6H5NO2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "nicotinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H5NO2/c8-6(9)5-2-1-3-7-4-5/h1-4H,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C6H6N2O", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxamide", "common_name": "nicotinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6N2O/c7-6(9)5-2-1-3-8-4-5/h1-4H,(H2,7,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C7H14O7", "iupac_name": "pentose", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11-1/h2-10H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C5H11NO4", "iupac_name": "ribosylamine", "common_name": "ribosylamine", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C11H11N3O4", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoylpyridinium riboside", "common_name": "nicotinamide riboside", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C7H5NO4", "iupac_name": "pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid", "common_name": "quinolinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C7H5NO4/c9-6(10)4-2-1-3-8-5(4)7(11)12/h1-3H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C6H7NO8P", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoyl-1-beta-D-ribofuranosylpyridinium 5-phosphate", "common_name": "nicotinamide mononucleotide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde-equivalent reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation furnishes reduced C1 carbonyl products that can feed formose-type homologation chemistry.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-bearing minerals are documented to reduce CO2 to small reduced organics under alkaline vent conditions, providing prebiotic carbonyl feedstocks for downstream sugar chemistry; used here as a literature-consistent connector into surface formose/cyanosulfidic networks rather than as a nicotinamide-specific step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface sugar homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed evaporitic pools; borate stabilizes sugars"}, "mechanism": "Formose-like aldehyde homologation and photoredox sugar generation produce C2 and C3 sugars, with borate stabilization of product pools.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde are established products of prebiotic photoredox/formose-related chemistry and are explicitly identified in cyanosulfidic protometabolism as feedstocks linked to nicotinamide synthesis; borate mineral stabilization is supported for ribose/sugar preservation (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of aspartate precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent chemistry with reductive amination and alpha-keto acid interconversion"}, "mechanism": "Iron-sulfur-catalyzed reductive amination/transamination networks generate amino acid pools including serine and aspartate precursors from hydrothermal carbon fixation products.", "reasoning": "The deep research notes iron-sulfur minerals as catalysts for pyruvate and related alpha-keto acid transformations generating aspartate precursors via reductive amination; aspartate is required for the Cleaves-Miller route, so this reaction connects hydrothermal metabolism-like chemistry to the biomimetic NAD pathway (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019; Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Phosphorylation and isomerization of glyceraldehyde to triose phosphates", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate-buffered evaporitic settings with wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated phosphorylation of C3 sugars followed by keto-enol isomerization yields glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller found phosphorylated substrates such as DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate give markedly higher yields in the non-enzymatic NAD de novo pathway; phosphate therefore has a catalytic and substrate-defining role in the network (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral-supported Cu(I)/Cu(II)-type photoredox proxy system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered near pH 7, cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox cyanation/coupling chemistry generates cyanoacetylene as a key nitrile feedstock for cyanoacetaldehyde production.", "reasoning": "The deep research explicitly identifies cyanoacetylene as a cyanosulfidic product linking Sutherland chemistry to nicotinamide synthesis, formed from HCN and acetylene under Cu(I)-driven conditions; mineral sulfides are included to satisfy the required surface mineral specification while keeping the chemistry aligned with the reported cyanosulfidic framework (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces assisting aqueous hydration and concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow aqueous pools, UV-exposed"}, "mechanism": "Aqueous hydration of cyanoacetylene furnishes cyanoacetaldehyde, the critical nexus molecule for pyridine-ring construction.", "reasoning": "Cyanoacetaldehyde formation by hydration of cyanoacetylene is directly described in the literature summary and is central to both Orgel-type nicotinonitrile synthesis and Trapp's NAD pathway; this molecule is the key nexus connecting cyanosulfidic chemistry to nicotinamide assembly (Dowler et al., 1970; Patel et al., 2015; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Electric-discharge generation of propiolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces in spark-discharge volcanic setting", "aqueous": "false", "other": "electric discharge on CH4/H2O or related volcanic atmospheric mixtures"}, "mechanism": "High-energy discharge chemistry furnishes propiolaldehyde as the second C3 carbonyl partner for Chichibabin-type pyridine synthesis.", "reasoning": "Propiolaldehyde was specifically reported as a discharge product and one of the two essential C3 precursors for the Dowler-Orgel-Sanchez route and the Trapp sequence; this is one of the best-supported entry points into nicotinamide ring formation (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporative concentration; anoxic ammonia-compatible conditions"}, "mechanism": "C3+C3 condensation gives the linear conjugated dialdehyde nitrile intermediate that branches toward nicotinonitrile or ribosylated nicotinonitrile.", "reasoning": "2-Cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde is the critical branch-point intermediate identified by Orgel and later used by Trapp for direct coupling to ribosylamine. Its formation from cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde is central to the literature-grounded network (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Chichibabin-type cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ammonia to nicotinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic/tidal concentration with NH3 present"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-promoted ring closure/aromatization of the dialdehyde nitrile forms pyridine-3-carbonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the defining Orgel/Dowler step for prebiotic access to the nicotinamide heterocycle precursor and remains one of the two principal experimentally demonstrated routes to the biologically relevant 3-substituted pyridine ring (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Stepwise hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide and nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "stepwise aqueous hydrolysis; partial hydrolysis stops at amide, complete hydrolysis reaches acid"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration gives the amide, and further hydrolysis yields the carboxylic acid; both products are reachable from the nitrile under aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. explicitly reported stepwise hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide and nicotinic acid. This reaction creates one major convergence point: both heterocycle-first routes and riboside-first routes can feed the same nicotinamide/nicotinic acid product pool (Dowler et al., 1970; Oba et al., 2022 for nicotinamide occurrence)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Ribose formation and stabilization in evaporitic surface settings", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "formose-like sugar network in borate-bearing geothermal fields"}, "mechanism": "C2/C3 sugars feed borate-stabilized pentose production, furnishing ribose for ribosylamine and nucleoside formation.", "reasoning": "The deep research specifically notes glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors for ribosylation and borate minerals as stabilizers of ribose under prebiotic conditions relevant to nicotinamide chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ammonolysis of ribose to ribosylamine", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild warming", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-stabilized evaporitic chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia premixed with ribose before aldehyde addition"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of ammonia with ribose gives ribosylamine, the glycosyl donor used directly in pyridine-ring-forming cyclization.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. showed that ribosylamine must be pre-formed by mixing ribose and ammonia before aldehyde precursors are added; otherwise only free nicotinonitrile forms. This procedural order is essential in the literature and is preserved here (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Direct cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ribosylamine to nicotinamide riboside precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild, near ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "evaporative mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia premixed with ribose; one-pot coupling/heterocyclization"}, "mechanism": "The branch-point dialdehyde reacts with ribosylamine to form nicotinonitrile riboside, which hydrolyzes within the same reaction network to nicotinamide riboside.", "reasoning": "This is the core Trapp-group innovation: coupling heterocycle formation and glycosylation in a single step through the 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde branch point, bypassing separate unstable nicotinamide ribosylation. The output is represented as the hydrolyzed nicotinamide riboside pool for network compactness (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "23C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ITO-P phosphorylation system with phosphate-rich setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 6, 7 days, regioselective 5'-phosphorylation, low yield (~2%)"}, "mechanism": "Activated phosphate transfer to the riboside gives nicotinamide mononucleotide while preserving the labile N-glycosidic bond under mild acidic conditions.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. reported regioselective 5'-phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside using ITO-P at pH 6 and 23C over 7 days to yield NMN. This step addresses the key glycosidic-bond bottleneck and is included exactly because the literature identifies it as the route to a stable redox-active nicotinamide nucleotide intermediate (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolytic cleavage of nicotinamide riboside or NMN to nicotinamide", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "reflects glycosidic bond lability of nicotinamide riboside under aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "Labile N-glycosidic bond hydrolysis liberates free nicotinamide from ribosylated nicotinamide derivatives.", "reasoning": "The deep research highlights the intrinsic lability of nicotinamide riboside, which hydrolyzes within hours at room temperature, and notes stabilization upon phosphorylation. This provides a literature-supported route from ribosylated intermediates back to free nicotinamide (Kim & Benner, 2018; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Biomimetic non-enzymatic assembly of quinolinic acid from aspartate and DHAP", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable aqueous prebiotic conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate-rich substrates enhance yield; non-enzymatic six-step analog"}, "mechanism": "Aspartate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate undergo a sequence analogous to the bacterial de novo NAD pathway, converging on quinolinic acid.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller demonstrated that the entire bacterial de novo route from aspartate + DHAP proceeds non-enzymatically to quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, with yields up to 7%, making this one of the strongest literature-grounded alternative routes to the nicotinamide scaffold (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable aqueous prebiotic conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "continuation of non-enzymatic de novo NAD sequence"}, "mechanism": "Decarboxylative/rearrangement steps within the biomimetic NAD pathway convert quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid.", "reasoning": "Quinolinic acid is explicitly the key heterocyclic intermediate in the Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic pathway, and nicotinic acid is the documented downstream product. Meteorite detection of both compounds also supports their prebiotic relevance (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Asparagine-analog direct route to nicotinamide from amino acid + triose phosphate chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable aqueous prebiotic conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "biomimetic variant of the Cleaves-Miller pathway representing direct amide-forming branch"}, "mechanism": "An amidated amino-acid/triose-phosphate pathway analogous to the asparagine substitution experiment yields the amide product directly without requiring nicotinic acid hydrolysis/amidation sequencing.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller reported that when asparagine replaced aspartate, nicotinamide was produced directly. Because asparagine itself is not separately defined in this compact network, serine/aspartate-amide precursor chemistry is used as the minimal connector while retaining the literature-grounded conclusion that an amidated amino-acid entry can lead directly to nicotinamide. This is the one intentionally compacted representation in the network and is therefore mildly schematic but literature-based (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Aqueous amidation equilibrium between nicotinic acid and nicotinamide", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild heating to ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "amide/acid interconversion represented as a connecting step to complete the nicotinamide pool"}, "mechanism": "Carboxyl activation/ammonolysis under prebiotic aqueous cycling is represented as a network-level conversion from nicotinic acid to nicotinamide.", "reasoning": "The literature clearly establishes both nicotinic acid and nicotinamide as members of the same prebiotic product family in laboratory and meteoritic settings; while direct prebiotic amidation conditions are less explicitly detailed than nitrile hydrolysis, this connector is necessary to unify the acid-producing Cleaves-Miller branch with the target nicotinamide pool and is therefore marked as a conservative network-completion step consistent with the observed co-occurrence of both compounds (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Oba et al., 2022; Oba et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "HCN hydration to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV photochemistry in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Hydration/photochemical conversion of HCN furnishes formamide, a general amidation/nitrogen-transfer reagent in prebiotic chemistry.", "reasoning": "HCN to formamide photochemistry is part of the broader surface prebiotic chemistry framework summarized in the instructions, and including formamide provides a literature-compatible amide donor pool that helps connect nitrile, acid, and amide nodes without contradicting nicotinamide-specific findings (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Orgel direct nicotinonitrile hydrolysis route", "description": "Cyanoacetylene-derived cyanoacetaldehyde condenses with discharge-derived propiolaldehyde; the resulting branch-point dialdehyde cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile, which partially hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal-carbon-fed Orgel route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface sugar chemistry and atmospheric/cyanosulfidic feedstocks, converging on the same Orgel nicotinonitrile branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Trapp ribosylamine-coupled route with hydrolytic release", "description": "The Orgel dialdehyde reacts with preformed ribosylamine to create nicotinamide riboside, whose labile glycosidic bond hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_020", "mol_021", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Trapp NMN branch with downstream cleavage to nicotinamide", "description": "Ribosylamine-coupled heterocycle formation is followed by 5'-phosphorylation to NMN; subsequent hydrolytic breakdown returns free nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_021", "mol_022", "mol_024"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cleaves-Miller de novo pathway via quinolinic acid", "description": "Hydrothermal amino-acid generation and surface phosphorylation provide aspartate and DHAP for the non-enzymatic bacterial-like pathway through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid and then nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_023", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cleaves-Miller direct amide branch", "description": "A biomimetic amidated amino-acid branch analogous to the asparagine substitution experiment furnishes nicotinamide directly from amino acid and DHAP chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Quinolinic-acid-first variant seeded by hydrothermal carbon", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon to sugar chemistry, which then enters triose phosphate formation and the quinolinic acid pathway to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_023", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Ribose-assisted surface route converging back through nicotinonitrile hydrolysis", "description": "Surface sugar chemistry generates ribose and ribosylamine, but if ribosylation is incomplete the same dialdehyde pool can instead cyclize with ammonia to nicotinonitrile and hydrolyze to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_021", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Nicotinic-acid reservoir to nicotinamide", "description": "Any route generating nicotinic acid, including Cleaves-Miller or nitrile overhydrolysis, can feed a shared nicotinic-acid reservoir that converts to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Meteorite-compatible mixed network route", "description": "This mixed pathway reflects the co-occurrence of quinolinic acid, nicotinic acid, and nicotinamide in extraterrestrial samples by combining the biomimetic quinolinate branch with amide-forming equilibration into the target pool.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_023", "mol_018"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_013", "mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_023", "mol_018"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_016", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_017", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_018", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_017"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_019", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": []}, {"molecule_id": "mol_023", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 145708.36806297302, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T16:07:04.500309", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Nicotinamide\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network uses literature-grounded convergent prebiotic routes to nicotinamide centered on two experimentally supported heterocycle-forming strategies: (1) the Orgel/Trapp C3+C3 condensation route through cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, and 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile, nicotinamide, and nicotinamide riboside; and (2) the Cleaves-Miller biomimetic aspartate + DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid and nicotinamide. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon hubs such as formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, pyruvate, and aspartate precursors; surface cyanosulfidic and evaporitic chemistry generates cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, ribose/ribosylamine, and phosphorylation capacity; biochemical/prebiotic steps complete amidation/hydrolysis and glycosylation-linked access to nicotinamide. Ten distinct pathways to nicotinamide are traced through shared hub molecules: cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, nicotinonitrile, quinolinic acid, and nicotinic acid.\n\nMOLECULES (25 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C3H7NO4 (aspartic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H7NO3 (serine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H7O6P (glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H7O6P (dihydroxyacetone phosphate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: HCN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H2 (acetylene) [starting]\n  - mol_012: C3HN (cyanoacetylene) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H3NO (cyanoacetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C3H2O (propiolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_016: C6H4NO2 (2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C6H4N2 (nicotinonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C6H5NO2 (nicotinic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C6H6N2O (nicotinamide) [target]\n  - mol_020: C7H14O7 (ribose) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_021: C5H11NO4 (ribosylamine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_022: C11H11N3O4 (nicotinamide riboside) [intermediate]\n  - mol_023: C7H5NO4 (quinolinic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_024: C6H7NO8P (nicotinamide mononucleotide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_025: CH4N2O (formamide) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (20 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde-equivalent reduced carbon) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_003 -> mol_004, mol_005 (Surface sugar homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002, mol_015 -> mol_006, mol_007 (Hydrothermal generation of aspartate precursor pool) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_005 -> mol_008, mol_009 (Phosphorylation and isomerization of glyceraldehyde to triose phosphates) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_010, mol_011 -> mol_012 (Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN and acetylene) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_012 -> mol_013 (Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011 -> mol_014 (Electric-discharge generation of propiolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_013, mol_014 -> mol_016 (Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_016, mol_015 -> mol_017 (Chichibabin-type cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ammonia to nicotinonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_017 -> mol_019, mol_018 (Stepwise hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide and nicotinic acid) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_020 (Ribose formation and stabilization in evaporitic surface settings) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_020, mol_015 -> mol_021 (Ammonolysis of ribose to ribosylamine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_016, mol_021 -> mol_022 (Direct cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ribosylamine to nicotinamide riboside precursor pool) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_022 -> mol_024 (Selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_022, mol_024 -> mol_019 (Hydrolytic cleavage of nicotinamide riboside or NMN to nicotinamide) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_006, mol_009 -> mol_023 (Biomimetic non-enzymatic assembly of quinolinic acid from aspartate and DHAP) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_017: mol_023 -> mol_018 (Conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_018: mol_007, mol_009 -> mol_019 (Asparagine-analog direct route to nicotinamide from amino acid + triose phosphate chemistry) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_019: mol_018, mol_015 -> mol_019 (Aqueous amidation equilibrium between nicotinic acid and nicotinamide) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_020: mol_010 -> mol_025 (HCN hydration to formamide) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Orgel direct nicotinonitrile hydrolysis route (6 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal-carbon-fed Orgel route (8 steps)\n  - P3: Trapp ribosylamine-coupled route with hydrolytic release (8 steps)\n  - P4: Trapp NMN branch with downstream cleavage to nicotinamide (9 steps)\n  - P5: Cleaves-Miller de novo pathway via quinolinic acid (6 steps)\n  - P6: Cleaves-Miller direct amide branch (4 steps)\n  - P7: Quinolinic-acid-first variant seeded by hydrothermal carbon (7 steps)\n  - P8: Ribose-assisted surface route converging back through nicotinonitrile hydrolysis (5 steps)\n  - P9: Nicotinic-acid reservoir to nicotinamide (2 steps)\n  - P10: Meteorite-compatible mixed network route (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_013, mol_016, mol_017, mol_023, mol_018\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide: from spark discharge to complete NAD\u207a assembly\n\n**Nicotinamide\u2014the redox-active heterocycle at the heart of NAD\u207a\u2014can be assembled prebiotically through at least three independent routes from simple feedstocks, and has been detected in pristine asteroid samples.** The field has progressed from Orgel's foundational propiolaldehyde\u2013cyanoacetaldehyde condensation (1970) to Trapp's complete prebiotic NAD\u207a synthesis (2024), while meteoritic detections in Ryugu and Bennu confirm extraterrestrial vitamin B\u2083 formation as a robust cosmochemical process. Two principal pathways to the pyridine ring dominate the literature: (1) a Chichibabin-type cyclization from C\u2083 aldehyde precursors and ammonia, producing nicotinonitrile, and (2) a non-enzymatic recapitulation of the bacterial aspartate\u2013DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid. Both operate under prebiotically plausible conditions, but the glycosidic bond instability of nicotinamide riboside and the concentration problem remain fundamental bottlenecks.\n\n## Two convergent routes to the pyridine ring\n\nThe first prebiotic access to the nicotinamide heterocycle was demonstrated by Dowler, Fuller, Orgel, and Sanchez (*Science* 169, 1320\u20131321, 1970). Their route combines **propiolaldehyde** (HC\u2261C\u2013CHO, produced by electric discharge on CH\u2084/H\u2082O mixtures) with **cyanoacetaldehyde** (NCCH\u2082CHO, formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene) and ammonia. The two C\u2083 units condense to form **2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde**, a linear intermediate that undergoes Chichibabin-type ring closure with ammonia to yield **nicotinonitrile** (3-cyanopyridine). Stepwise hydrolysis then gives nicotinamide (partial) or nicotinic acid (complete). The 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde intermediate has proven to be a critical branch-point molecule: in the presence of ribosylamine (from ribose + ammonia), it cyclizes directly to nicotinonitrile riboside, coupling heterocycle formation with glycosylation in a single step.\n\nFriedmann, Miller, and Sanchez (*Science* 171, 1026\u20131027, 1971) complemented this work by showing that electric discharge on **ethylene + ammonia** generates pyridine and HCN, which recombine to produce all three cyanopyridine isomers\u2014nicotinonitrile (3-position), 2-cyanopyridine, and 4-cyanopyridine. The preferential formation of the 3-isomer under certain conditions partially addresses the regioselectivity question of why biology uses the 3-carboxamide rather than the 2- or 4-isomer, though selectivity remains incomplete. Miyakawa, Cleaves, and Miller (*PNAS* 99, 14628\u201314631, 2002) later demonstrated that even mildly reducing **CO\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082\u2013H\u2082O atmospheres**\u2014more geochemically plausible than strongly reducing CH\u2084-rich mixtures\u2014produce nicotinic acid alongside amino acids and nucleobases under electric discharge and proton irradiation.\n\nThe second major pathway mirrors the most ancient biosynthetic route to NAD\u207a. Cleaves and Miller (*J. Mol. Evol.* 52, 73\u201377, 2001) showed that the entire six-step bacterial de novo pathway from **aspartic acid + dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP)** proceeds non-enzymatically through **quinolinic acid** (pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid) to nicotinic acid. Yields reached **up to 7%**\u2014remarkably high for prebiotic chemistry. Phosphorylated substrates (DHAP, glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate) gave significantly higher yields than their non-phosphorylated analogs, suggesting catalytic roles for phosphate. When asparagine replaced aspartate, nicotinamide was produced directly. This result established that NAD biosynthesis could have originated as \"an inevitable consequence of life based on carbohydrates and amino acids,\" with enzymes added later to each step independently.\n\n## From nicotinamide to NAD\u207a: the complete prebiotic pathway\n\nThe assembly of the full NAD\u207a dinucleotide requires three additional transformations beyond heterocycle synthesis: N-glycosylation, phosphorylation, and pyrophosphate coupling. Each presents distinct prebiotic challenges.\n\n**Glycosylation.** Kim and Benner (*Chem. Eur. J.* 24, 581\u2013584, 2018) achieved the first prebiotically plausible ribosylation by reacting nicotinamide with **ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate** in the presence of Mg\u00b2\u207a or Ca\u00b2\u207a at **85\u00b0C** under evaporative conditions. The cyclic phosphate blocks the \u03b1-face of ribose, enforcing stereoselective \u03b2-glycoside formation. However, the product is the **2\u2032-phosphate regioisomer** rather than the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN. Critically, the same chemistry produces adenosine 2\u2032-phosphate, unifying RNA nucleotide and NAD\u207a precursor synthesis under shared conditions.\n\n**The Trapp group breakthrough.** Bechtel, Kurrle, and Trapp (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202402055, 2024) reported the **first complete prebiotic synthesis of NAD\u207a** from simple feedstocks. Their pathway proceeds through four stages: (1) cyanoacetaldehyde + propiolaldehyde form 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde; (2) this intermediate cyclizes with ribosylamine (pre-formed from ribose + ammonia) to yield **nicotinonitrile riboside**, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside; (3) **regioselective 5\u2032-phosphorylation** using ITO-P (isothiatriazine-3-one phosphate, formed under Strecker-type conditions with H\u2082S) at pH 6, 23\u00b0C over 7 days gives **NMN at ~2% yield**; (4) photochemical coupling of NMN with ITO-AMP (light-activated adenylate) under **278 nm UV irradiation** forms the pyrophosphate bond to yield NAD\u207a. A key procedural insight was that ammonia must be pre-mixed with ribose before addition of the aldehyde precursors; reversing the order produces only free nicotinonitrile without ribosylation. The photochemical activation step draws directly on Sutherland's methyl isocyanide phosphorimidazolide chemistry (Mariani, Russell, Javelle, and Sutherland, *JACS* 140, 8657\u20138661, 2018).\n\n## Connection to cyanosulfidic protometabolism\n\nNeither the Sutherland group (MRC LMB Cambridge) nor the Powner group (UCL) has published a paper directly targeting nicotinamide synthesis. However, the cyanosulfidic protometabolic network described in Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (*Nature Chemistry* 7, 301\u2013307, 2015) generates exactly the feedstocks required. **Cyanoacetylene** (HC\u2083N), produced from HCN + acetylene via Cu(I)-catalyzed Nieuwland-type coupling, hydrates in water to form cyanoacetaldehyde\u2014a direct substrate for pyridine ring formation. **Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde** emerge from HCN photoredox chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, *Nature Chemistry* 4, 895\u2013899, 2012), providing both the sugar precursor for ribosylation and the C\u2083 carbonyl for the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway. The cyanosulfidic conditions\u2014HCN, H\u2082S, Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, UV irradiation, phosphate buffering at ~pH 7, ~35\u00b0C\u2014are broadly compatible with nicotinamide ring closure, making cyanoacetaldehyde the critical nexus molecule connecting Sutherland-type chemistry to NAD\u207a assembly.\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence validates prebiotic synthesis\n\nNicotinic acid (niacin) is now established as an indigenous component of carbonaceous chondrites and pristine asteroid samples. Smith, Callahan, Gerakines, Dworkin, and House (*Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 136, 1\u201312, 2014) systematically surveyed eight Antarctic CM2 meteorites and detected nicotinic acid at **30\u2013600 ppb** in all samples, alongside picolinic acid, isonicotinic acid, and\u2014for the first time in meteorites\u2014pyridine dicarboxylic acids including quinolinic acid. Abundance **negatively correlated** with the degree of pre-terrestrial aqueous alteration, suggesting parent-body processing degrades these compounds. Pizzarello and Huang (2004, 2005) provided isotopic proof of extraterrestrial origin for Murchison nicotinic acid: **\u03b4D = +129\u2030 and \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C = +20\u2030**, values far outside terrestrial ranges.\n\nThe Hayabusa2 mission delivered the most compelling evidence. Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 14, 1292, 2023) detected nicotinic acid at **49\u201399 ppb** in pristine, hermetically sealed Ryugu samples\u2014more abundant than uracil (6\u201332 ppb). The OSIRIS-REx analysis of asteroid Bennu (Glavin et al., *Nature Astronomy*, 2025) found nicotinic acid alongside all five canonical nucleobases, 14 amino acids, and ~10,000 N-bearing molecular species, with N-heterocycle concentrations **5\u201310\u00d7 higher than Ryugu**.\n\n**Nicotinamide itself** (not just nicotinic acid) was first detected in meteorites by Oba et al. (*Nature Communications* 13, 2008, 2022) using gentle room-temperature extraction and HPLC/ESI-HRMS on Murchison, Tagish Lake, and Murray samples. Previous studies missed nicotinamide because harsh acid hydrolysis conditions (6M HCl, 150\u00b0C) converted it entirely to nicotinic acid. This analytical insight resolved a long-standing gap and confirmed that both the amide and acid forms are present extraterrestrially. Isonicotinamide was co-detected, and the complete isomer suite (all positional isomers plus alkylated homologs) argues strongly against terrestrial contamination.\n\n## Interstellar ice chemistry as a formation mechanism\n\nSmith, Gerakines, and Callahan (*Chem. Commun.* 51, 11787\u201311790, 2015) demonstrated that proton irradiation of astrophysical ice analogs (H\u2082O:CO\u2082:pyridine = 100:20:1) produces nicotinic acid, quinolinic acid, and other pyridine carboxylic acids. In water-rich ices mimicking interstellar grain mantles, **nicotinic acid becomes the favored monocarboxylic acid isomer** (preferential 3-position carboxylation), and the product ratio (picolinic:isonicotinic:nicotinic \u2248 0.89:0.35:1.00) closely matches the least aqueously altered CM2 chondrites. This correspondence supports cosmic ray processing of N-heterocyclic ices as the primary formation mechanism, with subsequent parent-body aqueous alteration modifying the initial distribution.\n\nPaschek, Lee, Semenov, and Henning (*ChemPlusChem* 89, e202300508, 2024) modeled vitamin B\u2083 synthesis inside **carbonaceous planetesimals** using the Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway: Strecker-derived aspartate + formose-derived glyceraldehyde/DHA at 0\u2013100\u00b0C, ~100 bar, in anaerobic aqueous solution. Their thermochemical equilibrium predictions match measured meteorite abundances, and the mechanism correctly predicts the absence of picolinic acid (consistent with observed meteorite data).\n\nNeither pyridine nor nicotinic acid has been definitively detected in the interstellar medium via radio/millimeter-wave spectroscopy, despite extensive searches. The non-detection is attributed to rapid photodestruction, chemical conversion, and dilution across many structural isomers. However, the 2018 detection of benzonitrile (McGuire et al., *Science*) and subsequent identifications of cyanonaphthalene isomers in TMC-1 confirm that six-membered aromatic rings are present in the ISM.\n\n## Environmental conditions and mineral catalysis\n\nThe three principal prebiotic environments each favor different steps in nicotinamide and NAD\u207a synthesis. **Volcanic/surficial settings** provide electric discharge (volcanic lightning) for generating HCN, cyanoacetylene, and propiolaldehyde, plus UV irradiation for the photochemical NAD\u207a coupling step. The Bechtel/Kurrle/Trapp pathway is most compatible with this environment. **Evaporitic/tidal settings** support Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation chemistry, which requires evaporative drying at 80\u201390\u00b0C with divalent metal ion catalysis, and borate minerals that stabilize ribose. **Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (serpentinizing systems) excel at NAD\u207a reduction: Henriques Pereira et al. (*Communications Chemistry* 8, 318, 2025) showed that Ni-Fe mineral surfaces reduce NAD\u207a specifically to **1,4-NADH** using H\u2082 gas at 40\u00b0C, pH 8.5, 5 bar H\u2082, while NMN lacking the AMP moiety is overreduced to biologically useless products. The AMP \"handle\" of NAD\u207a thus serves a functional prebiotic role\u2014protecting against overreduction on mineral surfaces\u2014suggesting the dinucleotide structure predates enzymes.\n\nMineral catalysts relevant to specific steps include:\n\n- **Ni-Fe alloys** (awaruite, taenite): Catalyze stereospecific NAD\u207a \u2192 1,4-NADH reduction with H\u2082; NiFe\u2083 nanopowder outperforms pure metals by ~300%\n- **Iron-sulfur minerals** (pyrite, pyrrhotite): Catalyze pyruvate and related \u03b1-keto acid transformations, generating aspartate precursors via reductive amination\n- **Phosphate minerals**: Catalytic role in Cleaves\u2013Miller pathway (phosphorylated substrates yield significantly more nicotinic acid)\n- **Borate minerals**: Stabilize ribose for glycosylation chemistry\n- **Cu(I)/Cu(II)**: Drive photoredox cycling in cyanosulfidic networks, generating cyanoacetylene and sugar precursors\n\n## Critical bottlenecks and unresolved challenges\n\n**The glycosidic bond problem** remains the most severe. The N-glycosidic bond in nicotinamide riboside is intrinsically labile because the positively charged pyridinium ring acts as an excellent leaving group. Free nicotinamide riboside hydrolyzes within hours at room temperature. Kim and Benner showed that 2\u2032-phosphorylation stabilizes the nucleoside, while Bechtel et al. required carefully controlled mild conditions (pH 6, 23\u00b0C) to preserve the bond during 5\u2032-phosphorylation. Whether nicotinamide riboside can persist long enough under realistic geological conditions for downstream chemistry\u2014or whether all steps must be telescoped into one-pot sequences\u2014is unresolved.\n\n**Regiochemistry** presents a dual challenge. Electric discharge produces all three cyanopyridine isomers, not exclusively the biologically relevant 3-isomer. And while the Kim\u2013Benner ribosylation produces the 2\u2032-phosphate (not the biologically relevant 5\u2032-NMN), the Trapp group's ITO-P achieves 5\u2032-selective phosphorylation at the cost of low yields (~2%). No prebiotic equivalent of the biological PRPP-mediated 5\u2032-ribosylation has been demonstrated.\n\n**The concentration problem** constrains multi-component condensation reactions. The Orgel/Chichibabin cyclization requires simultaneous presence of propiolaldehyde, cyanoacetaldehyde, and ammonia at concentrations sufficient for efficient ring closure. Evaporative concentration in ponds or tidal flats offers a solution but restricts viable geological settings. **The water problem**\u2014thermodynamic unfavorability of condensation reactions in dilute aqueous solution\u2014affects glycosylation, phosphoester, and pyrophosphate bond formation. Bechtel et al. overcome the pyrophosphate step with photochemical energy input, but this requires surficial UV access incompatible with deep-sea hydrothermal vent models.\n\nSebastianelli, Kaur, Chen, Krishnamurthy, and Mansy (*Chem. Eur. J.* 30, e202400411, 2024) demonstrated that **free nicotinamide cannot accept electrons from pyruvate**\u2014only NMN and NAD\u207a support non-enzymatic redox cycling. The anomeric carbon (sugar attachment point) is essential for electron transfer. This places severe demands on prebiotic chemistry: the heterocycle alone is metabolically inert, and at minimum the complete nucleotide (NMN) must form before any useful redox chemistry can occur.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of nicotinamide has matured from isolated heterocycle formation to a complete, demonstrated pathway to NAD\u207a within five decades. The convergence of three independent lines of evidence\u2014laboratory synthesis, meteoritic detection, and astrophysical ice chemistry\u2014establishes nicotinic acid/nicotinamide as among the most prebiotically accessible cofactor precursors. The Orgel/Chichibabin route through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde and the Cleaves\u2013Miller biomimetic aspartate pathway represent genuinely distinct chemical strategies to the same heterocycle, operating under different but overlapping environmental conditions. The Trapp group's 2024 NAD\u207a synthesis marks a watershed, yet the field remains constrained by the fundamental tension between the lability of the nicotinamide glycosidic bond and the thermodynamic demands of building the full dinucleotide in water. The emerging functional evidence\u2014that the AMP handle protects against overreduction on mineral surfaces, and that free nicotinamide lacks redox activity\u2014reframes the problem: prebiotic chemistry must produce not merely the heterocycle, but the complete nucleotide, before NAD\u207a can participate in the protometabolic networks that origin-of-life models require. Whether this was achieved through one-pot telescoped sequences in geochemically structured environments, or through exogenous delivery of nicotinic acid followed by terrestrial ribosylation, remains the central open question.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true