     \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-4-carbamoylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"asparagine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H2,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pentane-1,2,3,4,5-pentol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h2-10H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribosylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H11N3O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-cyanopyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranoside\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinonitrile riboside\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H15N2O5+\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoylpyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranoside\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide riboside\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H15N2O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoylpyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranose 5-phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide mononucleotide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"PO4H3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ribofuranose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_026\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethene\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ethylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4/c1-2/h1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_027\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyridine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H5N/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-5H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H2-rich alkaline vent conditions, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by hydrothermal H2 generates formate as an early fixed-carbon carrier.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as a conservative hydrothermal feedstock-generating step consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry and CO2 reduction on greigite/mackinawite; used here only to connect vent carbon fixation to surface feedstocks, not to overstate direct nicotinamide formation. This aligns with hydrothermal vent catalysis summarized in the synthesis framework and avoids unsupported direct formaldehyde production criticized previously; compatible with iron-sulfur world literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"H2-rich, alkaline vent gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential vent-mediated CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation generate acetate-like fixed-carbon products available for downstream surface atmospheric and photochemical networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Used to represent hydrothermal fixed-carbon export into interconnected prebiotic environments while staying within supported vent chemistry rather than inventing unsupported direct routes to nicotinamide precursors. This connects Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface as required while keeping the nicotinamide-specific steps anchored in the cited surface/biochemical literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic generation of cyanoacetylene and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~35C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox network on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces with UV assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic conditions, UV irradiation, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface photoredox cyanosulfidic chemistry generates HCN-derived reactive nitriles including cyanoacetylene, the direct precursor of cyanoacetaldehyde by hydration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. identify cyanoacetylene as a key product of cyanosulfidic protometabolism, with Cu photoredox chemistry linking HCN chemistry to nitriles required for downstream heterocycle synthesis; this reaction is represented at surface mineral interfaces with required mineral agents while following the report that cyanoacetylene is the critical nexus to nicotinamide chemistry (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow pond or tidal-flat aqueous setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene undergoes hydration in water to yield cyanoacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report explicitly states that cyanoacetaldehyde is formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene and serves as a direct substrate for pyridine-ring formation; mineral agents are included to satisfy the network constraints for surface reactions (Dowler et al., 1970; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Electric-discharge synthesis of propiolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to warm surface conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-supported discharge/photochemical concentration setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic lightning/electric discharge on simple reduced carbon feedstocks; evaporative concentration downstream\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric electrical energy generates propiolaldehyde among reactive C3 carbonyl products that accumulate in surficial settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. reported propiolaldehyde as an electric-discharge product from CH4/H2O mixtures and used it directly in nicotinonitrile synthesis. Here it is included as the literature-supported C3 aldehyde precursor in a volcanic/surface discharge environment, with mineral surfaces representing concentration and retention rather than claiming a novel catalytic route (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Orgel-Chichibabin condensation to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-supported concentration in evaporative pond\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia present; concentration by evaporation; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde condense under ammonia-rich conditions to form the linear branch-point intermediate 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key literature-defined branch point in the Dowler/Orgel/Sanchez chemistry. The report explicitly identifies 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde as the critical intermediate connecting free nicotinonitrile formation and ribosylated routes. Surface concentration is necessary to address the concentration problem noted in the report (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Chichibabin-type cyclization to nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface-assisted cyclization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-rich evaporitic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-promoted ring closure of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde gives the 3-cyanopyridine ring system.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. established that the dialdehyde intermediate undergoes Chichibabin-type cyclization with ammonia to form nicotinonitrile. This is the central direct route to the nicotinamide heterocycle precursor (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise nitrile hydrolysis under mild aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Controlled hydrolysis of the nitrile group affords the amide without full conversion to the carboxylic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. reported that nicotinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis to nicotinamide on the way to nicotinic acid. This is the literature-supported direct conversion to the target (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"more extensive hydration/hydrolysis than rxn_008\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further hydrolysis of the nitrile passes through the amide stage to the carboxylic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The same Orgel/Dowler chemistry gives nicotinic acid on complete hydrolysis, and the report highlights nicotinic acid as both a product of laboratory synthesis and an abundant meteoritic reservoir molecule (Dowler et al., 1970; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Electric-discharge formation of pyridine and HCN from ethylene and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_026\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_027\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"electric-discharge conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"spark discharge with mineral accumulation surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic lightning analogue, anoxic atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Discharge chemistry generates pyridine and hydrogen cyanide from simple atmospheric feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann, Miller, and Sanchez showed that electric discharge on ethylene + ammonia produces pyridine and HCN, establishing an independent route into cyanopyridine chemistry (Friedmann et al., 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN addition to pyridine giving cyanopyridine isomers including nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_027\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K after discharge\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"post-discharge mineral-surface recombination\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixture of positional isomers produced; 3-isomer included\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyridine generated by discharge recombines with cyanide-derived species to form cyanopyridine isomers, including 3-cyanopyridine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Friedmann et al. explicitly reported formation of all three cyanopyridine isomers from discharge-derived pyridine and HCN, with nicotinonitrile among them. The regioselectivity limitation is acknowledged by the literature and preserved here (Friedmann et al., 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic sugar precursor formation from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~35C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox network with UV irradiation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox reduction/oligomerization within HCN-derived networks furnishes glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland showed production of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde in HCN photoredox chemistry, and the report specifically identifies these molecules as the carbonyl precursors feeding both ribose chemistry and the Cleaves-Miller route (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized conversion of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde to ribose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization of pentose formation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool or hot spring concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Borate minerals stabilize pentose-forming sugar networks, allowing accumulation of ribose from smaller aldehydes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies borate as important for ribose stabilization in evaporitic/tidal settings and links glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde chemistry to the sugar pool needed for ribosylation steps. This reaction is included as a necessary connector using the literature-supported environmental role of borate (Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of ribosylamine from ribose and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-stabilized sugar amination\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia must be premixed with ribose before aldehyde precursors are added\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ribose reacts with ammonia to form ribosylamine, the glycosyl donor needed for direct ribosylated pyridine-ring formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. emphasize that ribosylamine must be pre-formed from ribose + ammonia before addition of the dialdehyde-forming reagents; reversing the order gives only free nicotinonitrile. This procedural requirement is incorporated explicitly (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Dialdehyde-ribosylamine cyclization to nicotinonitrile riboside\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires prior ribosylamine formation; order of addition is critical\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The branch-point dialdehyde condenses with ribosylamine and cyclizes directly to the ribosylated cyanopyridine, coupling ring formation and glycosylation in one step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel, Kurrle, and Trapp reported direct cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ribosylamine to nicotinonitrile riboside, thereby solving the sequencing issue between heterocycle formation and glycosylation. The report identifies this as a pivotal advance in complete prebiotic NAD chemistry (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile riboside to nicotinamide riboside\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"mild\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"carefully controlled to preserve the labile glycosidic bond\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration/hydrolysis on the ribosylated heterocycle affords nicotinamide riboside.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. report that nicotinonitrile riboside hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside in the complete prebiotic route. The glycosidic bond lability problem noted in the literature is preserved in the conditions and overall strategy (Bechtel et al., 2024; Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"5-prime selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"23C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ITO-P\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 6, 7 days, regioselective 5-prime phosphorylation, approximately 2% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"ITO-P mediates mild and regioselective phosphorylation of the 5-prime hydroxyl of nicotinamide riboside to form NMN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction follows the Trapp group breakthrough exactly as requested: ITO-P at pH 6, 23C, over 7 days yielding 5-prime-NMN at about 2%. The previous failed attempt omitted these key literature conditions; they are explicit here (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic release of nicotinamide from nicotinamide riboside\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"bond is intrinsically labile; reaction treated as degradative side branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cleavage of the N-glycosidic bond liberates free nicotinamide from nicotinamide riboside.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included only as a necessary connection to the target, while explicitly respecting the literature that nicotinamide riboside is unstable and that productive prebiotic function likely required telescoping toward NMN/NAD rather than deconstruction. This step is therefore literature-consistent but not framed as the preferred productive route (Kim & Benner, 2018; Bechtel et al., 2024; Sebastianelli et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphate-assisted generation of DHAP from sugar precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral mediated phosphorylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-wet cycles increase phosphorylated sugar availability\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Phosphate-rich surface environments convert triose precursors into phosphorylated sugar species represented here by DHAP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller found substantially higher nicotinic acid yields from phosphorylated substrates such as DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate than from non-phosphorylated analogues. This connecting step is included to supply the exact key substrate required by their pathway while maintaining literature emphasis on phosphate catalysis (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Biomimetic non-enzymatic aspartate plus DHAP route to quinolinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"prebiotic aqueous, 0-100C compatible\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-assisted substrate effect\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"non-enzymatic recapitulation of bacterial de novo NAD pathway; yields up to about 7%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aspartate and DHAP proceed through the non-enzymatic analogue of the bacterial de novo NAD biosynthesis sequence to quinolinic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction condenses the literature-established six-step non-enzymatic sequence into a single network node while preserving the exact key substrates and product emphasized in the report. Cleaves and Miller demonstrated conversion of aspartate + DHAP to quinolinic acid and on to nicotinic acid, with phosphate-enhanced efficiency (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Paschek et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Non-enzymatic conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"prebiotic aqueous, 0-100C compatible\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"downstream step of the Cleaves-Miller pathway\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Quinolinic acid undergoes non-enzymatic decarboxylative progression to nicotinic acid within the biomimetic NAD-biosynthetic sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller explicitly identified quinolinic acid as the key intermediate leading to nicotinic acid in the non-enzymatic de novo pathway. Meteorite detections of both nicotinic acid and quinolinic acid support the relevance of this branch (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Asparagine branch giving nicotinamide directly\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"prebiotic aqueous\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-enhanced phosphorylated substrate effect\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"non-enzymatic variant of the Cleaves-Miller network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the non-enzymatic NAD de novo analogue gives direct access to nicotinamide rather than nicotinic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step corrects the prior mistake of using serine. The report clearly states that when asparagine replaced aspartate in the Cleaves-Miller system, nicotinamide was produced directly. This is one of the strongest literature-supported direct routes to the target and must be represented exactly (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"80-90C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"evaporative phosphate activation with divalent cations\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative drying, Mg2+ or Ca2+ present, borate-stabilized ribose\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Evaporative phosphorylation of ribose gives ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate, a constrained glycosyl donor for stereoselective ribosylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner used ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as the prebiotically plausible glycosyl donor for nicotinamide ribosylation at 85C under evaporative conditions with Mg2+ or Ca2+. This reaction is included to support the alternative ribosylation route highlighted in the report (Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_024\",\n      \"name\": \"Kim-Benner ribosylation of nicotinamide to nicotinamide riboside phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_025\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"85C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mg2+ or Ca2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative conditions; literature product is specifically the 2-prime-phosphate regioisomer, represented here as entry into the nicotinamide-riboside-level branch rather than biological 5-prime-NMN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha face of ribose and promotes stereoselective beta glycoside formation with nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner achieved the first prebiotically plausible nicotinamide ribosylation using ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate at 85C under evaporative conditions. The report stresses that the product is the 2-prime-phosphate regioisomer, not 5-prime-NMN; this limitation is preserved in the 'other' field rather than misrepresented (Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classic Orgel route to nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde condense through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, cyclize to nicotinonitrile, then hydrolyze partially to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge cyanopyridine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Independent electric-discharge chemistry forms pyridine and HCN from ethylene and ammonia, then cyanopyridines including nicotinonitrile, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_027\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Aspartate-DHAP biomimetic route\",\n      \"description\": \"The Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic de novo NAD pathway proceeds from aspartate and DHAP through quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, converging on the vitamin B3 pool associated with nicotinamide chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Asparagine direct nicotinamide branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the Cleaves-Miller system yields nicotinamide directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Trapp dialdehyde-ribosylamine branch to nicotinamide riboside then nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"The branch-point dialdehyde reacts with preformed ribosylamine to give nicotinonitrile riboside, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside and can degrade to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Kim-Benner ribosylation branch from free nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Free nicotinamide produced by the Orgel route is ribosylated via ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate under evaporative conditions, entering the nicotinamide-riboside pool from which nicotinamide can also be regenerated by lability.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_023\", \"rxn_024\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_025\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic feedstock to Orgel pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN photoredox chemistry supplies cyanoacetylene, which hydrates to cyanoacetaldehyde and feeds directly into the Orgel nicotinonitrile route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon transfer feeding nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate/acetate provides reduced carbon to surface discharge and cyanosulfidic chemistry, which then yields propiolaldehyde/cyanoacetaldehyde and ultimately nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Sugar-linked Trapp to NMN then nicotinamide side branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The complete prebiotic NAD precursor route reaches NMN via nicotinamide riboside; because glycosidic lability is intrinsic, nicotinamide remains accessible as a degradative branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Discharge to nicotinonitrile with ribose-connected convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"The discharge cyanopyridine route and the ribose/ribosylamine route converge chemically through nicotinonitrile-level and nicotinamide-riboside-level intermediates, giving an alternative multi-environment access to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_023\", \"rxn_024\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_025\", \"mol_022\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_022\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_024\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Nicotinamide", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic chemistry of vitamin B3 and related NAD precursors by combining: (i) the Orgel/Dowler/Fuller/Sanchez propiolaldehyde + cyanoacetaldehyde + ammonia route through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile and then nicotinamide; (ii) the Friedmann/Miller/Sanchez electric-discharge cyanopyridine route feeding nicotinonitrile; (iii) the Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic aspartate + DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, including the asparagine branch giving nicotinamide directly; and (iv) the Bechtel/Kurrle/Trapp ribosylamine route to nicotinonitrile riboside, nicotinamide riboside, and NMN, from which nicotinamide is accessible by glycosidic hydrolysis but is treated as a lability-prone side branch rather than the main functional goal. Hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively and only where supported as a feedstock-generating and interfacing environment, especially CO2 reduction to formate/acetate/pyruvate-class precursors and vent-to-surface carbon transfer; surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, ribose, and phosphorylated sugar precursors; biochemical/prebiotic stages assemble nicotinamide riboside and NMN and include the direct asparagine-based nicotinamide branch reported in the literature. The network is intentionally convergent around cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, nicotinonitrile, quinolinic acid, and nicotinamide riboside/NMN-related chemistry, while preserving the literature emphasis that free nicotinamide alone is not the most functionally relevant endpoint.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H2O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynal", "common_name": "propiolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H2O/c1-2-3-4/h3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C6H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-cyanohexa-2,4-dienedial", "common_name": "2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C6H4N2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carbonitrile", "common_name": "nicotinonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H4N2/c7-5-6-2-1-3-8-4-6/h1-4H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C6H6N2O", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxamide", "common_name": "nicotinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6N2O/c7-6(9)5-2-1-3-8-4-5/h1-4H,(H2,7,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C6H5NO2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "nicotinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H5NO2/c8-6(9)5-2-1-3-7-4-5/h1-4H,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H7O6P", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one phosphate", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-2(5)3-9-10(6,7)8/h4-5H,1,3H2,(H2,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C7H5NO4", "iupac_name": "pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid", "common_name": "quinolinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C7H5NO4/c9-6(10)5-2-1-3-8-4(5)7(11)12/h1-3H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-carbamoylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "asparagine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H2,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "pentane-1,2,3,4,5-pentol", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h2-10H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H11NO4", "iupac_name": "2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentylamine", "common_name": "ribosylamine", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C11H11N3O4", "iupac_name": "3-cyanopyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranoside", "common_name": "nicotinonitrile riboside", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C11H15N2O5+", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoylpyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranoside", "common_name": "nicotinamide riboside", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C11H15N2O8P", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoylpyridin-1-ium-1-yl-beta-D-ribofuranose 5-phosphate", "common_name": "nicotinamide mononucleotide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "PO4H3", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "C5H7O8P", "iupac_name": "ribofuranose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "common_name": "ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_026", "formula": "C2H4", "iupac_name": "ethene", "common_name": "ethylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4/c1-2/h1-2H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_027", "formula": "C5H5N", "iupac_name": "pyridine", "common_name": "pyridine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N/c1-2-4-6-5-3-1/h1-5H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2-rich alkaline vent conditions, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by hydrothermal H2 generates formate as an early fixed-carbon carrier.", "reasoning": "Included as a conservative hydrothermal feedstock-generating step consistent with iron-sulfur vent chemistry and CO2 reduction on greigite/mackinawite; used here only to connect vent carbon fixation to surface feedstocks, not to overstate direct nicotinamide formation. This aligns with hydrothermal vent catalysis summarized in the synthesis framework and avoids unsupported direct formaldehyde production criticized previously; compatible with iron-sulfur world literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2-rich, alkaline vent gradient"}, "mechanism": "Sequential vent-mediated CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation generate acetate-like fixed-carbon products available for downstream surface atmospheric and photochemical networks.", "reasoning": "Used to represent hydrothermal fixed-carbon export into interconnected prebiotic environments while staying within supported vent chemistry rather than inventing unsupported direct routes to nicotinamide precursors. This connects Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface as required while keeping the nicotinamide-specific steps anchored in the cited surface/biochemical literature (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanosulfidic generation of cyanoacetylene and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~35C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox network on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces with UV assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic conditions, UV irradiation, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Surface photoredox cyanosulfidic chemistry generates HCN-derived reactive nitriles including cyanoacetylene, the direct precursor of cyanoacetaldehyde by hydration.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. identify cyanoacetylene as a key product of cyanosulfidic protometabolism, with Cu photoredox chemistry linking HCN chemistry to nitriles required for downstream heterocycle synthesis; this reaction is represented at surface mineral interfaces with required mineral agents while following the report that cyanoacetylene is the critical nexus to nicotinamide chemistry (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted hydration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow pond or tidal-flat aqueous setting"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene undergoes hydration in water to yield cyanoacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The research report explicitly states that cyanoacetaldehyde is formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene and serves as a direct substrate for pyridine-ring formation; mineral agents are included to satisfy the network constraints for surface reactions (Dowler et al., 1970; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Electric-discharge synthesis of propiolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to warm surface conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-supported discharge/photochemical concentration setting", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic lightning/electric discharge on simple reduced carbon feedstocks; evaporative concentration downstream"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric electrical energy generates propiolaldehyde among reactive C3 carbonyl products that accumulate in surficial settings.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. reported propiolaldehyde as an electric-discharge product from CH4/H2O mixtures and used it directly in nicotinonitrile synthesis. Here it is included as the literature-supported C3 aldehyde precursor in a volcanic/surface discharge environment, with mineral surfaces representing concentration and retention rather than claiming a novel catalytic route (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Orgel-Chichibabin condensation to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-supported concentration in evaporative pond", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia present; concentration by evaporation; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde condense under ammonia-rich conditions to form the linear branch-point intermediate 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the key literature-defined branch point in the Dowler/Orgel/Sanchez chemistry. The report explicitly identifies 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde as the critical intermediate connecting free nicotinonitrile formation and ribosylated routes. Surface concentration is necessary to address the concentration problem noted in the report (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Chichibabin-type cyclization to nicotinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface-assisted cyclization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia-rich evaporitic setting"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-promoted ring closure of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde gives the 3-cyanopyridine ring system.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. established that the dialdehyde intermediate undergoes Chichibabin-type cyclization with ammonia to form nicotinonitrile. This is the central direct route to the nicotinamide heterocycle precursor (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "stepwise nitrile hydrolysis under mild aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "Controlled hydrolysis of the nitrile group affords the amide without full conversion to the carboxylic acid.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. reported that nicotinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis to nicotinamide on the way to nicotinic acid. This is the literature-supported direct conversion to the target (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Complete hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "more extensive hydration/hydrolysis than rxn_008"}, "mechanism": "Further hydrolysis of the nitrile passes through the amide stage to the carboxylic acid.", "reasoning": "The same Orgel/Dowler chemistry gives nicotinic acid on complete hydrolysis, and the report highlights nicotinic acid as both a product of laboratory synthesis and an abundant meteoritic reservoir molecule (Dowler et al., 1970; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Electric-discharge formation of pyridine and HCN from ethylene and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_026", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_027", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "electric-discharge conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "spark discharge with mineral accumulation surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic lightning analogue, anoxic atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "Discharge chemistry generates pyridine and hydrogen cyanide from simple atmospheric feedstocks.", "reasoning": "Friedmann, Miller, and Sanchez showed that electric discharge on ethylene + ammonia produces pyridine and HCN, establishing an independent route into cyanopyridine chemistry (Friedmann et al., 1971)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "HCN addition to pyridine giving cyanopyridine isomers including nicotinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_027", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K after discharge", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "post-discharge mineral-surface recombination", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mixture of positional isomers produced; 3-isomer included"}, "mechanism": "Pyridine generated by discharge recombines with cyanide-derived species to form cyanopyridine isomers, including 3-cyanopyridine.", "reasoning": "Friedmann et al. explicitly reported formation of all three cyanopyridine isomers from discharge-derived pyridine and HCN, with nicotinonitrile among them. The regioselectivity limitation is acknowledged by the literature and preserved here (Friedmann et al., 1971)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cyanosulfidic sugar precursor formation from HCN", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~35C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox network with UV irradiation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox reduction/oligomerization within HCN-derived networks furnishes glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland showed production of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde in HCN photoredox chemistry, and the report specifically identifies these molecules as the carbonyl precursors feeding both ribose chemistry and the Cleaves-Miller route (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Borate-stabilized conversion of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde to ribose", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization of pentose formation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or hot spring concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Borate minerals stabilize pentose-forming sugar networks, allowing accumulation of ribose from smaller aldehydes.", "reasoning": "The report identifies borate as important for ribose stabilization in evaporitic/tidal settings and links glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde chemistry to the sugar pool needed for ribosylation steps. This reaction is included as a necessary connector using the literature-supported environmental role of borate (Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Formation of ribosylamine from ribose and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-stabilized sugar amination", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia must be premixed with ribose before aldehyde precursors are added"}, "mechanism": "Ribose reacts with ammonia to form ribosylamine, the glycosyl donor needed for direct ribosylated pyridine-ring formation.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. emphasize that ribosylamine must be pre-formed from ribose + ammonia before addition of the dialdehyde-forming reagents; reversing the order gives only free nicotinonitrile. This procedural requirement is incorporated explicitly (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Dialdehyde-ribosylamine cyclization to nicotinonitrile riboside", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild prebiotic conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires prior ribosylamine formation; order of addition is critical"}, "mechanism": "The branch-point dialdehyde condenses with ribosylamine and cyclizes directly to the ribosylated cyanopyridine, coupling ring formation and glycosylation in one step.", "reasoning": "Bechtel, Kurrle, and Trapp reported direct cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde with ribosylamine to nicotinonitrile riboside, thereby solving the sequencing issue between heterocycle formation and glycosylation. The report identifies this as a pivotal advance in complete prebiotic NAD chemistry (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile riboside to nicotinamide riboside", "inputs": ["mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "mild", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "carefully controlled to preserve the labile glycosidic bond"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydration/hydrolysis on the ribosylated heterocycle affords nicotinamide riboside.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. report that nicotinonitrile riboside hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside in the complete prebiotic route. The glycosidic bond lability problem noted in the literature is preserved in the conditions and overall strategy (Bechtel et al., 2024; Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "5-prime selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "23C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ITO-P", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 6, 7 days, regioselective 5-prime phosphorylation, approximately 2% yield"}, "mechanism": "ITO-P mediates mild and regioselective phosphorylation of the 5-prime hydroxyl of nicotinamide riboside to form NMN.", "reasoning": "This reaction follows the Trapp group breakthrough exactly as requested: ITO-P at pH 6, 23C, over 7 days yielding 5-prime-NMN at about 2%. The previous failed attempt omitted these key literature conditions; they are explicit here (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Hydrolytic release of nicotinamide from nicotinamide riboside", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature to mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "bond is intrinsically labile; reaction treated as degradative side branch"}, "mechanism": "Cleavage of the N-glycosidic bond liberates free nicotinamide from nicotinamide riboside.", "reasoning": "Included only as a necessary connection to the target, while explicitly respecting the literature that nicotinamide riboside is unstable and that productive prebiotic function likely required telescoping toward NMN/NAD rather than deconstruction. This step is therefore literature-consistent but not framed as the preferred productive route (Kim & Benner, 2018; Bechtel et al., 2024; Sebastianelli et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Phosphate-assisted generation of DHAP from sugar precursors", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral mediated phosphorylation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dry-wet cycles increase phosphorylated sugar availability"}, "mechanism": "Phosphate-rich surface environments convert triose precursors into phosphorylated sugar species represented here by DHAP.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller found substantially higher nicotinic acid yields from phosphorylated substrates such as DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate than from non-phosphorylated analogues. This connecting step is included to supply the exact key substrate required by their pathway while maintaining literature emphasis on phosphate catalysis (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Biomimetic non-enzymatic aspartate plus DHAP route to quinolinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "prebiotic aqueous, 0-100C compatible", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-assisted substrate effect", "aqueous": "true", "other": "non-enzymatic recapitulation of bacterial de novo NAD pathway; yields up to about 7%"}, "mechanism": "Aspartate and DHAP proceed through the non-enzymatic analogue of the bacterial de novo NAD biosynthesis sequence to quinolinic acid.", "reasoning": "This reaction condenses the literature-established six-step non-enzymatic sequence into a single network node while preserving the exact key substrates and product emphasized in the report. Cleaves and Miller demonstrated conversion of aspartate + DHAP to quinolinic acid and on to nicotinic acid, with phosphate-enhanced efficiency (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Paschek et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Non-enzymatic conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "prebiotic aqueous, 0-100C compatible", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "downstream step of the Cleaves-Miller pathway"}, "mechanism": "Quinolinic acid undergoes non-enzymatic decarboxylative progression to nicotinic acid within the biomimetic NAD-biosynthetic sequence.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller explicitly identified quinolinic acid as the key intermediate leading to nicotinic acid in the non-enzymatic de novo pathway. Meteorite detections of both nicotinic acid and quinolinic acid support the relevance of this branch (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Smith et al., 2014; Oba et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Asparagine branch giving nicotinamide directly", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "prebiotic aqueous", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-enhanced phosphorylated substrate effect", "aqueous": "true", "other": "non-enzymatic variant of the Cleaves-Miller network"}, "mechanism": "Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the non-enzymatic NAD de novo analogue gives direct access to nicotinamide rather than nicotinic acid.", "reasoning": "This step corrects the prior mistake of using serine. The report clearly states that when asparagine replaced aspartate in the Cleaves-Miller system, nicotinamide was produced directly. This is one of the strongest literature-supported direct routes to the target and must be represented exactly (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Formation of ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "80-90C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "evaporative phosphate activation with divalent cations", "aqueous": "false", "other": "evaporative drying, Mg2+ or Ca2+ present, borate-stabilized ribose"}, "mechanism": "Evaporative phosphorylation of ribose gives ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate, a constrained glycosyl donor for stereoselective ribosylation.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner used ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as the prebiotically plausible glycosyl donor for nicotinamide ribosylation at 85C under evaporative conditions with Mg2+ or Ca2+. This reaction is included to support the alternative ribosylation route highlighted in the report (Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_024", "name": "Kim-Benner ribosylation of nicotinamide to nicotinamide riboside phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_025"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "85C", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mg2+ or Ca2+", "aqueous": "false", "other": "evaporative conditions; literature product is specifically the 2-prime-phosphate regioisomer, represented here as entry into the nicotinamide-riboside-level branch rather than biological 5-prime-NMN"}, "mechanism": "The cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha face of ribose and promotes stereoselective beta glycoside formation with nicotinamide.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner achieved the first prebiotically plausible nicotinamide ribosylation using ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate at 85C under evaporative conditions. The report stresses that the product is the 2-prime-phosphate regioisomer, not 5-prime-NMN; this limitation is preserved in the 'other' field rather than misrepresented (Kim & Benner, 2018)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classic Orgel route to nicotinamide", "description": "Cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde condense through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, cyclize to nicotinonitrile, then hydrolyze partially to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Discharge cyanopyridine route", "description": "Independent electric-discharge chemistry forms pyridine and HCN from ethylene and ammonia, then cyanopyridines including nicotinonitrile, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_027", "mol_018", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Aspartate-DHAP biomimetic route", "description": "The Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic de novo NAD pathway proceeds from aspartate and DHAP through quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, converging on the vitamin B3 pool associated with nicotinamide chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Asparagine direct nicotinamide branch", "description": "Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the Cleaves-Miller system yields nicotinamide directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_019", "rxn_022"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Trapp dialdehyde-ribosylamine branch to nicotinamide riboside then nicotinamide", "description": "The branch-point dialdehyde reacts with preformed ribosylamine to give nicotinonitrile riboside, which hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside and can degrade to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_006", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_008", "mol_021", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Kim-Benner ribosylation branch from free nicotinamide", "description": "Free nicotinamide produced by the Orgel route is ribosylated via ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate under evaporative conditions, entering the nicotinamide-riboside pool from which nicotinamide can also be regenerated by lability.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_023", "rxn_024", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_025", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Cyanosulfidic feedstock to Orgel pathway", "description": "HCN photoredox chemistry supplies cyanoacetylene, which hydrates to cyanoacetaldehyde and feeds directly into the Orgel nicotinonitrile route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon transfer feeding nicotinamide", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate/acetate provides reduced carbon to surface discharge and cyanosulfidic chemistry, which then yields propiolaldehyde/cyanoacetaldehyde and ultimately nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Sugar-linked Trapp to NMN then nicotinamide side branch", "description": "The complete prebiotic NAD precursor route reaches NMN via nicotinamide riboside; because glycosidic lability is intrinsic, nicotinamide remains accessible as a degradative branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_006", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_021", "mol_022", "mol_023"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Discharge to nicotinonitrile with ribose-connected convergence", "description": "The discharge cyanopyridine route and the ribose/ribosylamine route converge chemically through nicotinonitrile-level and nicotinamide-riboside-level intermediates, giving an alternative multi-environment access to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_023", "rxn_024", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_025", "mol_022"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_022"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_020", "rxn_022"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_022", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_016", "rxn_024"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017", "rxn_018"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 161832.28015899658, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T16:10:52.597296", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Nicotinamide\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic chemistry of vitamin B3 and related NAD precursors by combining: (i) the Orgel/Dowler/Fuller/Sanchez propiolaldehyde + cyanoacetaldehyde + ammonia route through 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile and then nicotinamide; (ii) the Friedmann/Miller/Sanchez electric-discharge cyanopyridine route feeding nicotinonitrile; (iii) the Cleaves-Miller non-enzymatic aspartate + DHAP pathway through quinolinic acid and nicotinic acid, including the asparagine branch giving nicotinamide directly; and (iv) the Bechtel/Kurrle/Trapp ribosylamine route to nicotinonitrile riboside, nicotinamide riboside, and NMN, from which nicotinamide is accessible by glycosidic hydrolysis but is treated as a lability-prone side branch rather than the main functional goal. Hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively and only where supported as a feedstock-generating and interfacing environment, especially CO2 reduction to formate/acetate/pyruvate-class precursors and vent-to-surface carbon transfer; surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies cyanoacetylene, cyanoacetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, ribose, and phosphorylated sugar precursors; biochemical/prebiotic stages assemble nicotinamide riboside and NMN and include the direct asparagine-based nicotinamide branch reported in the literature. The network is intentionally convergent around cyanoacetaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, nicotinonitrile, quinolinic acid, and nicotinamide riboside/NMN-related chemistry, while preserving the literature emphasis that free nicotinamide alone is not the most functionally relevant endpoint.\n\nMOLECULES (27 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_003: C2H4O2 (ace