 \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C7H5NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"quinolinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C7H5NO4/c9-6(10)5-3-1-2-8-4(5)7(11)12/h1-3H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7O6P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroxyacetone phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-2(5)3(6)9-10(7,8)11/h1,4H2,(H2,7,8,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pentane-1,2,3,4,5-pentol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h2-10H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentan-1-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribosylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H11N3O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoyl-1-(beta-D-ribofuranosyl)pyridinium\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide riboside\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H13N2O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-carbamoyl-1-(2-phosphono-beta-D-ribofuranosyl)pyridinium\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nicotinamide riboside 2'-phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C11H15N2O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"beta-nicotinamide mononucleotide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"NMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_026\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9O7P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_027\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H15N5O10P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"adenosine monophosphate activated by isothiatriazine phosphate chemistry\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ITO-AMP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_028\",\n      \"formula\": \"C18H27N7O14P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"NAD+\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_029\",\n      \"formula\": \"C18H28N7O14P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,4-dihydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1,4-NADH\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_030\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H10O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formose sugars pool\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to a one-carbon reduced carboxylate pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S minerals are established catalysts for CO2 reduction to formate and related C1 products in alkaline vent analogues, providing a realistic reduced-carbon feedstock that connects vent chemistry to later surface synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, H2-rich, pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction and C-C bond formation from reduced C1 species on Fe-S/oxide surfaces yields acetate-like products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate formation under hydrothermal mineral catalysis is consistent with Fe-S world and vent carbon-fixation analog chemistry and is included here only as a literature-supported environmental connector to broader organosynthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic subseafloor hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-promoted multicarbon fixation generates alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids can arise under hydrothermal mineral catalysis and provide a plausible feeder pool for prebiotic amino-acid synthesis, linking vent geochemistry to the aspartate/asparagine branch required by Cleaves-Miller chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination and carboxylation to aspartate pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"nonenzymatic amino-acid pool generation at mineral-water interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid amination/carboxylation sequence expands hydrothermal keto-acid pools into dicarboxylic amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is a necessary connector rather than a directly demonstrated single-step literature transformation to nicotinamide; it is included conservatively to bridge validated hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry to the experimentally supported aspartate-dependent quinolinate route. Aspartate itself is the substrate used in the nonenzymatic NAD biosynthesis analogue (Cleaves & Miller, 2001), and pyruvate/amino-acid network expansion is supported by prebiotic keto-acid chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Aspartate amidation to asparagine pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"condensation in concentrated prebiotic pools; included as network connector to the Cleaves-Miller asparagine branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amidation of the side-chain carboxylate generates the amide-bearing substrate analogous to the direct nicotinamide-forming branch.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller explicitly reported that replacing aspartate with asparagine in the nonenzymatic pathway produces nicotinamide directly. This reaction is included only to connect broader prebiotic amino-acid pools to that literature-supported branch; the amidation itself remains more speculative than the downstream conversion (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN feedstock\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic network, phosphate-buffered near pH 7\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived photoredox network generates higher nitriles including cyanoacetylene under Cu-mediated sulfide chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. described cyanosulfidic protometabolism furnishing the feedstocks required for nucleotide and heterocycle synthesis; cyanoacetylene is generated in this framework and is the direct precursor to cyanoacetaldehyde by hydration. Mineral agents reflect the required sulfide-rich photoredox setting specified in the network instructions (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"water-rich surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene hydrates to the beta-oxo nitrile cyanoacetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde is a key nexus molecule in nicotinamide chemistry and is formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene in the literature summary connecting Sutherland-type networks to Orgel/Trapp pyridine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Electric discharge generation of propiolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-rich evaporitic/surficial collection after electric discharge production\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"volcanic lightning/electric discharge atmosphere, followed by condensation into surface reservoirs\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric discharge chemistry generates propiolaldehyde, which is trapped in surface waters or evaporitic pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. used propiolaldehyde produced by electric discharge on CH4/H2O mixtures as a validated precursor for nicotinonitrile formation. This step is represented as atmospheric production feeding surface collection, with mineral surfaces concentrating the product rather than serving as the primary energetic driver (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration in evaporitic pools\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-bearing, concentrated surficial setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A C3+C3 condensation generates the linear dialdehyde nitrile branch-point intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Dowler-Orgel route identifies 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde as the crucial linear intermediate formed from propiolaldehyde and cyanoacetaldehyde before pyridine ring closure; Bechtel et al. later used the same branch-point in full NAD+ assembly (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Chichibabin-type cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surface concentration under anoxic surficial conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"ammonia must be available; evaporative concentration improves yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-promoted Chichibabin-type ring closure of the linear dialdehyde nitrile forms 3-cyanopyridine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core Orgel heterocycle-forming step. Dowler et al. showed that the dialdehyde intermediate cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile; regioselective access to the 3-isomer is central to the nicotinamide problem (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"controlled hydration; partial nitrile hydrolysis favored over full oxidation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration/hydrolysis gives the carboxamide without proceeding fully to the acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dowler et al. explicitly reported that nicotinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis to nicotinamide on the way to nicotinic acid; this is the most direct literature-supported route to the target heterocycle (Dowler et al., 1970).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted prolonged aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"further hydration beyond the amide stage\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Extended nitrile hydrolysis converts the carboxamide-equivalent intermediate to the free acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Orgel route yields nicotinic acid upon full hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile. This branch is included because nicotinic acid is a major experimentally and meteoritically validated reservoir of vitamin B3 chemistry and a convergence point with quinolinate chemistry (Dowler et al., 1970; Oba et al., 2023; Smith et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered around pH 7, H2S present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-derived photoredox homologation furnishes the key two- and three-carbon sugar precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland demonstrated prebiotic photoredox generation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, and Patel et al. embedded this in a broader cyanosulfidic network. These molecules are the literature-supported carbohydrate feeders into ribose and phosphorylated substrate formation relevant to nicotinamide/NAD chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized formose/aldol route to ribose-rich sugar pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_030\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pools with wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose chemistry expands lower sugars to pentoses, with borate stabilizing ribose-containing pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors and borate minerals as stabilizers of ribose for glycosylation chemistry. This step connects the cyanosulfidic carbohydrate network to both Trapp and Kim-Benner ribosylation branches (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose and ammonia condensation to ribosylamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-stabilized sugar pool on clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"ammonia must be premixed with ribose before aldehyde precursors are added\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammoniation of the open-chain sugar gives ribosylamine, enabling telescoped heterocycle formation with glycosylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. emphasized that ammonia must be pre-mixed with ribose to form ribosylamine before introduction of the dialdehyde precursor; otherwise only free nicotinonitrile forms. This ordering is critical and is preserved here (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"One-pot formation of nicotinamide riboside via nicotinonitrile riboside intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration in mild aqueous medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"ribosylamine preformed; cyclization gives nicotinonitrile riboside followed by hydrolysis to nicotinamide riboside\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The dialdehyde branch-point reacts with ribosylamine so that ring closure and glycosylation occur together, producing a ribosylated cyanopyridine that hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the key Trapp breakthrough: 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde cyclizes with ribosylamine directly to nicotinonitrile riboside, which then hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside. It is one of the strongest literature-supported bridges from heterocycle chemistry to nucleotide assembly (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Kim-Benner evaporative ribosylation to nicotinamide riboside 2'-phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_026\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Mg2+ or Ca2+ under evaporative conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"85C drying chemistry; cyclic phosphate blocks alpha-face and enforces beta-glycoside formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"N-glycosylation of nicotinamide by ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate yields the stabilized beta riboside 2'-phosphate regioisomer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner did not obtain free nicotinamide riboside; they obtained the 2'-phosphate product under evaporative 85C conditions with divalent cations. That exact product identity is preserved here to avoid the error noted in earlier failed attempts (Kim & Benner, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Regioselective 5'-phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"296K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ITO-P\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 6, 23C, 7 days, mild conditions; low yield around 2%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated phosphate transfer selectively installs the 5'-phosphate on the labile riboside under unusually mild conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. specifically used ITO-P at pH 6 and 23C for 7 days to achieve 5'-selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN at about 2% yield. These exact literature-sensitive conditions are included because omission of ITO-P was a major flaw in prior attempts (Bechtel et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical pyrophosphate coupling of NMN to NAD+\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_027\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_028\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"278 nm UV irradiation; photochemical coupling with light-activated adenylate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven activation enables pyrophosphate bond formation between NMN and activated AMP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bechtel et al. completed the first prebiotic NAD+ synthesis by coupling NMN with ITO-AMP under 278 nm UV light, drawing on Sutherland phosphorimidazolide activation chemistry. This step is included because the report emphasizes that the complete nucleotide is functionally more relevant than free nicotinamide (Bechtel et al., 2024; Mariani et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal mineral reduction of NAD+ to 1,4-NADH\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_028\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_029\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-Fe alloy-like vent minerals represented within reduced iron/sulfide hydrothermal setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8.5; stereospecific reduction to 1,4-NADH in alkaline vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen-driven mineral-surface hydride transfer selectively reduces the nicotinamide ring in NAD+.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Henriques Pereira et al. showed stereospecific reduction of NAD+ to 1,4-NADH on Ni-Fe minerals at 40C, pH 8.5, and 5 bar H2, while NMN was overreduced. This strongly supports the functional importance of the complete dinucleotide in hydrothermal settings. The mineral list is constrained by the schema, so reduced iron/sulfide hydrothermal agents are used to represent the vent context while citing the actual Ni-Fe result (Henriques Pereira et al., 2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Nonenzymatic aspartate plus DHAP pathway to quinolinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"phosphorylated substrates favored; phosphate enhances yields; nonenzymatic multi-step sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A biomimetic analogue of the bacterial de novo NAD pathway converts aspartate and DHAP through several uncatalyzed intermediates to quinolinic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller demonstrated that the bacterial de novo pathway from aspartate and DHAP can proceed nonenzymatically through quinolinic acid, with phosphorylated substrates giving substantially higher yields. This is one of the two principal literature-validated routes to vitamin B3 chemistry (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Nonenzymatic conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"continuation of the Cleaves-Miller nonenzymatic pathway\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Decarboxylative progression along the biomimetic NAD biosynthesis analogue furnishes nicotinic acid from quinolinate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cleaves and Miller showed that the nonenzymatic pathway proceeds through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid in yields up to about 7%, establishing nicotinic acid as a robust prebiotic convergence product (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Asparagine plus DHAP route to nicotinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"phosphorylated carbohydrate substrate; direct amide-forming branch\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the nonenzymatic de novo pathway analogue preserves ring assembly while delivering the carboxamide product directly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction strictly follows the literature correction requested by the failure analysis: Cleaves and Miller reported direct nicotinamide formation when asparagine replaced aspartate. No serine substitution is used here (Cleaves & Miller, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_024\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphate-assisted formation of DHAP-like phosphorylated triose pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-rich drying and rehydration cycles\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"phosphorylated triose generation/connectivity step included because Cleaves-Miller found phosphorylated substrates markedly superior\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface phosphorylation of a triose precursor furnishes the DHAP-class substrate required for the biomimetic quinolinate pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report stresses that DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate were much more effective than nonphosphorylated analogues in the Cleaves-Miller system. This connector is included to ensure network continuity from the cyanosulfidic sugar pool to the validated phosphorylated-substrate pathway, while acknowledging that exact prebiotic DHAP synthesis remains an open systems-chemistry challenge (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Orgel nicotinonitrile-to-nicotinamide pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface C3+C3 condensation gives the dialdehyde intermediate, which cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile and hydrolyzes partially to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic sugars feeding Trapp ribosylamine branch to nicotinamide riboside and nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN photoredox supplies sugars, ribose forms ribosylamine, and the Trapp one-pot heterocycle/glycosylation route passes through nicotinamide riboside, which is connected to the target pool through the shared nicotinamide node.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Kim-Benner nicotinamide ribosylation branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Preformed nicotinamide reacts with ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate under evaporative conditions to give the stabilized 2'-phosphate riboside derivative.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Trapp complete nucleotide assembly branch from the Orgel dialdehyde intermediate\",\n      \"description\": \"The dialdehyde reacts with ribosylamine to give nicotinamide riboside, which is phosphorylated with ITO-P to NMN and can continue to NAD+.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_025\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Full prebiotic NAD+ assembly followed by hydrothermal redox activation\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface synthesis builds NMN and NAD+, then hydrothermal mineral reduction generates 1,4-NADH, illustrating Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical interconnection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_025\", \"mol_028\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cleaves-Miller aspartate-DHAP to quinolinate to nicotinic acid branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation feeds amino-acid pools; surface phosphorylation supplies DHAP; the nonenzymatic de novo NAD analogue yields quinolinate and nicotinic acid.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_024\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Cleaves-Miller asparagine branch to nicotinamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Aspartate is converted to asparagine, which with DHAP gives nicotinamide directly in the reported nonenzymatic pathway analogue.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_024\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hybrid hydrothermal-surface route to nicotinamide via nicotinonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal acetate/formate production supports atmospheric/surface precursor availability, while the Orgel cyclization supplies nicotinamide through nicotinonitrile hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent surface route to nicotinamide through shared dialdehyde hub\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetaldehyde from cyanosulfidic chemistry and propiolaldehyde from discharge chemistry meet at 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, then proceed to nicotinamide.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative vitamin B3 convergence: nicotinic acid reservoir and nicotinamide direct branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The network shows two parallel vitamin B3 outcomes from distinct routes: nicotinic acid via quinolinate or full nitrile hydrolysis, and nicotinamide directly via either nicotinonitrile partial hydrolysis or the asparagine-DHAP branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_024\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_021\", \"rxn_023\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Nicotinamide", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic routes to nicotinamide centered on two experimentally established convergent heterocycle-forming strategies: (i) the Orgel/Trapp C3+C3 route through cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, and nicotinonitrile; and (ii) the Cleaves-Miller biomimetic aspartate plus DHAP route through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid, with the direct asparagine branch to nicotinamide. Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies cyanoacetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, ribose, and phosphorylated carbohydrate precursors; hydrothermal chemistry supplies formate, acetate, pyruvate, and amino-acid precursor pools that connect to aspartate/asparagine formation; biochemical/prebiotic steps assemble ribosides and nucleotides. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated by combining these validated cores with different feeder and downstream branches, while preserving the critical literature conditions for Kim-Benner ribosylation, Bechtel-Kurrle-Trapp NMN/NAD+ assembly, and Cleaves-Miller quinolinate chemistry. The network is designed so that nicotinamide is reached directly by nicotinonitrile hydrolysis or by the asparagine-dependent nonenzymatic NAD biosynthesis analogue, while also showing that ribosylated/nucleotide forms are functionally important intermediates rather than simple degradative dead ends.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetic acid/acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid/pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid/aspartate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-carbamoylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "asparagine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(7)6/h2H,1,5H2,(H2,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2HN", "iupac_name": "ethynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H3NO", "iupac_name": "3-oxopropanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3NO/c4-2-1-3-5/h1,3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H2O", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynal", "common_name": "propiolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H2O/c1-2-3-4/h3H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C6H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-cyanohexa-2,4-dienedial", "common_name": "2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H4N2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carbonitrile", "common_name": "nicotinonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H4N2/c7-4-6-2-1-3-8-5-6/h1-3,5H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H5NO2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxamide", "common_name": "nicotinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6N2O/c7-6(9)5-2-1-3-8-4-5/h1-4H,(H2,7,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H5NO2", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "nicotinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H5NO2/c8-6(9)5-2-1-3-7-4-5/h1-4H,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C7H5NO4", "iupac_name": "pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid", "common_name": "quinolinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C7H5NO4/c9-6(10)5-3-1-2-8-4(5)7(11)12/h1-3H,(H,9,10)(H,11,12)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C3H7O6P", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one phosphate", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7O6P/c4-1-2(5)3(6)9-10(7,8)11/h1,4H2,(H2,7,8,11)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "pentane-1,2,3,4,5-pentol", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h2-10H,1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H11NO4", "iupac_name": "2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentan-1-amine", "common_name": "ribosylamine", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C11H11N3O4", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoyl-1-(beta-D-ribofuranosyl)pyridinium", "common_name": "nicotinamide riboside", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C11H13N2O8P", "iupac_name": "3-carbamoyl-1-(2-phosphono-beta-D-ribofuranosyl)pyridinium", "common_name": "nicotinamide riboside 2'-phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "C11H15N2O8P", "iupac_name": "beta-nicotinamide mononucleotide", "common_name": "NMN", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_026", "formula": "C5H9O7P", "iupac_name": "ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "common_name": "ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_027", "formula": "C10H15N5O10P2", "iupac_name": "adenosine monophosphate activated by isothiatriazine phosphate chemistry", "common_name": "ITO-AMP", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_028", "formula": "C18H27N7O14P2", "iupac_name": "nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide", "common_name": "NAD+", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_029", "formula": "C18H28N7O14P2", "iupac_name": "1,4-dihydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide", "common_name": "1,4-NADH", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_030", "formula": "C6H10O5", "iupac_name": "2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentanal", "common_name": "formose sugars pool", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to a one-carbon reduced carboxylate pool.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S minerals are established catalysts for CO2 reduction to formate and related C1 products in alkaline vent analogues, providing a realistic reduced-carbon feedstock that connects vent chemistry to later surface synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, H2-rich, pH gradient"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction and C-C bond formation from reduced C1 species on Fe-S/oxide surfaces yields acetate-like products.", "reasoning": "Acetate formation under hydrothermal mineral catalysis is consistent with Fe-S world and vent carbon-fixation analog chemistry and is included here only as a literature-supported environmental connector to broader organosynthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic subseafloor hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-promoted multicarbon fixation generates alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate and related alpha-keto acids can arise under hydrothermal mineral catalysis and provide a plausible feeder pool for prebiotic amino-acid synthesis, linking vent geochemistry to the aspartate/asparagine branch required by Cleaves-Miller chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive amination and carboxylation to aspartate pool", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "nonenzymatic amino-acid pool generation at mineral-water interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto acid amination/carboxylation sequence expands hydrothermal keto-acid pools into dicarboxylic amino acids.", "reasoning": "This step is a necessary connector rather than a directly demonstrated single-step literature transformation to nicotinamide; it is included conservatively to bridge validated hydrothermal keto-acid chemistry to the experimentally supported aspartate-dependent quinolinate route. Aspartate itself is the substrate used in the nonenzymatic NAD biosynthesis analogue (Cleaves & Miller, 2001), and pyruvate/amino-acid network expansion is supported by prebiotic keto-acid chemistry (Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aspartate amidation to asparagine pool", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "condensation in concentrated prebiotic pools; included as network connector to the Cleaves-Miller asparagine branch"}, "mechanism": "Amidation of the side-chain carboxylate generates the amide-bearing substrate analogous to the direct nicotinamide-forming branch.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller explicitly reported that replacing aspartate with asparagine in the nonenzymatic pathway produces nicotinamide directly. This reaction is included only to connect broader prebiotic amino-acid pools to that literature-supported branch; the amidation itself remains more speculative than the downstream conversion (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of cyanoacetylene from HCN feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic network, phosphate-buffered near pH 7"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived photoredox network generates higher nitriles including cyanoacetylene under Cu-mediated sulfide chemistry.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. described cyanosulfidic protometabolism furnishing the feedstocks required for nucleotide and heterocycle synthesis; cyanoacetylene is generated in this framework and is the direct precursor to cyanoacetaldehyde by hydration. Mineral agents reflect the required sulfide-rich photoredox setting specified in the network instructions (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydration of cyanoacetylene to cyanoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydration", "aqueous": true, "other": "water-rich surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene hydrates to the beta-oxo nitrile cyanoacetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Cyanoacetaldehyde is a key nexus molecule in nicotinamide chemistry and is formed by hydration of cyanoacetylene in the literature summary connecting Sutherland-type networks to Orgel/Trapp pyridine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Electric discharge generation of propiolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-rich evaporitic/surficial collection after electric discharge production", "aqueous": false, "other": "volcanic lightning/electric discharge atmosphere, followed by condensation into surface reservoirs"}, "mechanism": "Atmospheric discharge chemistry generates propiolaldehyde, which is trapped in surface waters or evaporitic pools.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. used propiolaldehyde produced by electric discharge on CH4/H2O mixtures as a validated precursor for nicotinonitrile formation. This step is represented as atmospheric production feeding surface collection, with mineral surfaces concentrating the product rather than serving as the primary energetic driver (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Condensation of cyanoacetaldehyde and propiolaldehyde to 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration in evaporitic pools", "aqueous": true, "other": "ammonia-bearing, concentrated surficial setting"}, "mechanism": "A C3+C3 condensation generates the linear dialdehyde nitrile branch-point intermediate.", "reasoning": "The Dowler-Orgel route identifies 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde as the crucial linear intermediate formed from propiolaldehyde and cyanoacetaldehyde before pyridine ring closure; Bechtel et al. later used the same branch-point in full NAD+ assembly (Dowler et al., 1970; Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Chichibabin-type cyclization of 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde to nicotinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface concentration under anoxic surficial conditions", "aqueous": true, "other": "ammonia must be available; evaporative concentration improves yield"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-promoted Chichibabin-type ring closure of the linear dialdehyde nitrile forms 3-cyanopyridine.", "reasoning": "This is the core Orgel heterocycle-forming step. Dowler et al. showed that the dialdehyde intermediate cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile; regioselective access to the 3-isomer is central to the nicotinamide problem (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinamide", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "controlled hydration; partial nitrile hydrolysis favored over full oxidation"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydration/hydrolysis gives the carboxamide without proceeding fully to the acid.", "reasoning": "Dowler et al. explicitly reported that nicotinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis to nicotinamide on the way to nicotinic acid; this is the most direct literature-supported route to the target heterocycle (Dowler et al., 1970)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Complete hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile to nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted prolonged aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "further hydration beyond the amide stage"}, "mechanism": "Extended nitrile hydrolysis converts the carboxamide-equivalent intermediate to the free acid.", "reasoning": "The Orgel route yields nicotinic acid upon full hydrolysis of nicotinonitrile. This branch is included because nicotinic acid is a major experimentally and meteoritically validated reservoir of vitamin B3 chemistry and a convergence point with quinolinate chemistry (Dowler et al., 1970; Oba et al., 2023; Smith et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox formation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, phosphate-buffered around pH 7, H2S present"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived photoredox homologation furnishes the key two- and three-carbon sugar precursors.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland demonstrated prebiotic photoredox generation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, and Patel et al. embedded this in a broader cyanosulfidic network. These molecules are the literature-supported carbohydrate feeders into ribose and phosphorylated substrate formation relevant to nicotinamide/NAD chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Borate-stabilized formose/aldol route to ribose-rich sugar pool", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_030"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization and clay concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "evaporitic pools with wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose chemistry expands lower sugars to pentoses, with borate stabilizing ribose-containing pools.", "reasoning": "The deep research report identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sugar precursors and borate minerals as stabilizers of ribose for glycosylation chemistry. This step connects the cyanosulfidic carbohydrate network to both Trapp and Kim-Benner ribosylation branches (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015; Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Ribose and ammonia condensation to ribosylamine", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-stabilized sugar pool on clay surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "ammonia must be premixed with ribose before aldehyde precursors are added"}, "mechanism": "Ammoniation of the open-chain sugar gives ribosylamine, enabling telescoped heterocycle formation with glycosylation.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. emphasized that ammonia must be pre-mixed with ribose to form ribosylamine before introduction of the dialdehyde precursor; otherwise only free nicotinonitrile forms. This ordering is critical and is preserved here (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "One-pot formation of nicotinamide riboside via nicotinonitrile riboside intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration in mild aqueous medium", "aqueous": true, "other": "ribosylamine preformed; cyclization gives nicotinonitrile riboside followed by hydrolysis to nicotinamide riboside"}, "mechanism": "The dialdehyde branch-point reacts with ribosylamine so that ring closure and glycosylation occur together, producing a ribosylated cyanopyridine that hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside.", "reasoning": "This follows the key Trapp breakthrough: 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde cyclizes with ribosylamine directly to nicotinonitrile riboside, which then hydrolyzes to nicotinamide riboside. It is one of the strongest literature-supported bridges from heterocycle chemistry to nucleotide assembly (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Kim-Benner evaporative ribosylation to nicotinamide riboside 2'-phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_026"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Mg2+ or Ca2+ under evaporative conditions", "aqueous": false, "other": "85C drying chemistry; cyclic phosphate blocks alpha-face and enforces beta-glycoside formation"}, "mechanism": "N-glycosylation of nicotinamide by ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate yields the stabilized beta riboside 2'-phosphate regioisomer.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner did not obtain free nicotinamide riboside; they obtained the 2'-phosphate product under evaporative 85C conditions with divalent cations. That exact product identity is preserved here to avoid the error noted in earlier failed attempts (Kim & Benner, 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Regioselective 5'-phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN", "inputs": ["mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "296K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ITO-P", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 6, 23C, 7 days, mild conditions; low yield around 2%"}, "mechanism": "Activated phosphate transfer selectively installs the 5'-phosphate on the labile riboside under unusually mild conditions.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. specifically used ITO-P at pH 6 and 23C for 7 days to achieve 5'-selective phosphorylation of nicotinamide riboside to NMN at about 2% yield. These exact literature-sensitive conditions are included because omission of ITO-P was a major flaw in prior attempts (Bechtel et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Photochemical pyrophosphate coupling of NMN to NAD+", "inputs": ["mol_025", "mol_027"], "outputs": ["mol_028"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "278 nm UV irradiation; photochemical coupling with light-activated adenylate"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven activation enables pyrophosphate bond formation between NMN and activated AMP.", "reasoning": "Bechtel et al. completed the first prebiotic NAD+ synthesis by coupling NMN with ITO-AMP under 278 nm UV light, drawing on Sutherland phosphorimidazolide activation chemistry. This step is included because the report emphasizes that the complete nucleotide is functionally more relevant than free nicotinamide (Bechtel et al., 2024; Mariani et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Hydrothermal mineral reduction of NAD+ to 1,4-NADH", "inputs": ["mol_028", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_029"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313K", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni-Fe alloy-like vent minerals represented within reduced iron/sulfide hydrothermal setting", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8.5; stereospecific reduction to 1,4-NADH in alkaline vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Hydrogen-driven mineral-surface hydride transfer selectively reduces the nicotinamide ring in NAD+.", "reasoning": "Henriques Pereira et al. showed stereospecific reduction of NAD+ to 1,4-NADH on Ni-Fe minerals at 40C, pH 8.5, and 5 bar H2, while NMN was overreduced. This strongly supports the functional importance of the complete dinucleotide in hydrothermal settings. The mineral list is constrained by the schema, so reduced iron/sulfide hydrothermal agents are used to represent the vent context while citing the actual Ni-Fe result (Henriques Pereira et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Nonenzymatic aspartate plus DHAP pathway to quinolinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "phosphorylated substrates favored; phosphate enhances yields; nonenzymatic multi-step sequence"}, "mechanism": "A biomimetic analogue of the bacterial de novo NAD pathway converts aspartate and DHAP through several uncatalyzed intermediates to quinolinic acid.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller demonstrated that the bacterial de novo pathway from aspartate and DHAP can proceed nonenzymatically through quinolinic acid, with phosphorylated substrates giving substantially higher yields. This is one of the two principal literature-validated routes to vitamin B3 chemistry (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Nonenzymatic conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "continuation of the Cleaves-Miller nonenzymatic pathway"}, "mechanism": "Decarboxylative progression along the biomimetic NAD biosynthesis analogue furnishes nicotinic acid from quinolinate.", "reasoning": "Cleaves and Miller showed that the nonenzymatic pathway proceeds through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid in yields up to about 7%, establishing nicotinic acid as a robust prebiotic convergence product (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Asparagine plus DHAP route to nicotinamide", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient to moderate", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "phosphorylated carbohydrate substrate; direct amide-forming branch"}, "mechanism": "Substituting asparagine for aspartate in the nonenzymatic de novo pathway analogue preserves ring assembly while delivering the carboxamide product directly.", "reasoning": "This reaction strictly follows the literature correction requested by the failure analysis: Cleaves and Miller reported direct nicotinamide formation when asparagine replaced aspartate. No serine substitution is used here (Cleaves & Miller, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_024", "name": "Phosphate-assisted formation of DHAP-like phosphorylated triose pool", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-rich drying and rehydration cycles", "aqueous": true, "other": "phosphorylated triose generation/connectivity step included because Cleaves-Miller found phosphorylated substrates markedly superior"}, "mechanism": "Surface phosphorylation of a triose precursor furnishes the DHAP-class substrate required for the biomimetic quinolinate pathway.", "reasoning": "The report stresses that DHAP and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate were much more effective than nonphosphorylated analogues in the Cleaves-Miller system. This connector is included to ensure network continuity from the cyanosulfidic sugar pool to the validated phosphorylated-substrate pathway, while acknowledging that exact prebiotic DHAP synthesis remains an open systems-chemistry challenge (Cleaves & Miller, 2001; Patel et al., 2015)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct Orgel nicotinonitrile-to-nicotinamide pathway", "description": "Surface C3+C3 condensation gives the dialdehyde intermediate, which cyclizes with ammonia to nicotinonitrile and hydrolyzes partially to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic sugars feeding Trapp ribosylamine branch to nicotinamide riboside and nicotinamide", "description": "HCN photoredox supplies sugars, ribose forms ribosylamine, and the Trapp one-pot heterocycle/glycosylation route passes through nicotinamide riboside, which is connected to the target pool through the shared nicotinamide node.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_009", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021", "mol_022", "mol_013", "mol_023"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Kim-Benner nicotinamide ribosylation branch", "description": "Preformed nicotinamide reacts with ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate under evaporative conditions to give the stabilized 2'-phosphate riboside derivative.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_024"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Trapp complete nucleotide assembly branch from the Orgel dialdehyde intermediate", "description": "The dialdehyde reacts with ribosylamine to give nicotinamide riboside, which is phosphorylated with ITO-P to NMN and can continue to NAD+.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_009", "rxn_016", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021", "mol_022", "mol_013", "mol_023", "mol_025"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Full prebiotic NAD+ assembly followed by hydrothermal redox activation", "description": "Surface synthesis builds NMN and NAD+, then hydrothermal mineral reduction generates 1,4-NADH, illustrating Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical interconnection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_009", "rxn_016", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_023", "mol_025", "mol_028"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cleaves-Miller aspartate-DHAP to quinolinate to nicotinic acid branch", "description": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation feeds amino-acid pools; surface phosphorylation supplies DHAP; the nonenzymatic de novo NAD analogue yields quinolinate and nicotinic acid.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_024", "rxn_021", "rxn_022"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_018", "mol_017", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Direct Cleaves-Miller asparagine branch to nicotinamide", "description": "Aspartate is converted to asparagine, which with DHAP gives nicotinamide directly in the reported nonenzymatic pathway analogue.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_013", "rxn_024", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hybrid hydrothermal-surface route to nicotinamide via nicotinonitrile", "description": "Hydrothermal acetate/formate production supports atmospheric/surface precursor availability, while the Orgel cyclization supplies nicotinamide through nicotinonitrile hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Convergent surface route to nicotinamide through shared dialdehyde hub", "description": "Cyanoacetaldehyde from cyanosulfidic chemistry and propiolaldehyde from discharge chemistry meet at 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, then proceed to nicotinamide.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Alternative vitamin B3 convergence: nicotinic acid reservoir and nicotinamide direct branch", "description": "The network shows two parallel vitamin B3 outcomes from distinct routes: nicotinic acid via quinolinate or full nitrile hydrolysis, and nicotinamide directly via either nicotinonitrile partial hydrolysis or the asparagine-DHAP branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_012", "rxn_023", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_016", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_013", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_023"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_007", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_021"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_018", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_024"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_021", "rxn_023"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 166070.42503356934, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T16:18:27.144386", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Nicotinamide\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic routes to nicotinamide centered on two experimentally established convergent heterocycle-forming strategies: (i) the Orgel/Trapp C3+C3 route through cyanoacetaldehyde, propiolaldehyde, 2-cyanoglutaconic dialdehyde, and nicotinonitrile; and (ii) the Cleaves-Miller biomimetic aspartate plus DHAP route through quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid, with the direct asparagine branch to nicotinamide. Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry supplies cyanoacetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, ribose, and phosphorylated carbohydrate precursors; hydrothermal chemistry supplies formate, acetate, pyruvate, and amino-acid precursor pools that connect to aspartate/asparagine formation; biochemical/prebiotic steps assemble ribosides and nucleotides. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated by combining these validated cores with different feeder and downstream branches, while preserving the critical literature conditions for Kim-Benner ribosylation, Bechtel-Kurrle-Trapp NMN/NAD+ assembly, and Cleaves-Miller quinolinate chemistry. The network is designed so that nicotinamide is reached directly by nicotinonitrile hydrolysis or by the asparagine-dependent nonenzymatic NAD biosynthesis analogue, while also showing that ribosylated/nucleotide forms are functionally important intermediates rather than simple degradative dead ends.\n\nMOLECULES (30 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: CH2O2 (formic acid/formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: C2H4O2 (acetic acid/acetate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid/pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_007: C4H7NO4 (aspartic acid/aspartate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C4H8N2O3 (aspar