ause it reaches a functional redox cofactor and then hydrothermal reduction to 1,4-NADH. The reduction concept is literature-supported, but the network misses the crucial Ni-Fe alloy specificity and the fact that NAD+ reduction is favored whereas NMN is overreduced. The NMN formation issue remains the main bottleneck. Still, the environmental progression from surface assembly to hydrothermal redox activation is excellent.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_018\",\n        \"rxn_020\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify Ni-Fe alloy/awaruite-like catalysts, pH 8.5, 5 bar H2, and 40 C for NAD+ reduction.\",\n        \"Note that free nicotinamide is redox-inactive and that the NAD+ stage is functionally important.\",\n        \"Repair the upstream NMN step to make the full pathway literature-faithful.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.46,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_022\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.81,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"This branch aligns well with the Cleaves-Miller nonenzymatic pathway from aspartate plus DHAP to quinolinic acid and then nicotinic acid. The problematic element is the upstream abstraction of aspartate formation from pyruvate, ammonia, and CO2 in a single biochemical step; that is too compressed and not directly literature-matched. Once aspartate and DHAP are available, the pathway is strong.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_004\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand aspartate formation into oxaloacetate generation plus transamination/reductive amination steps.\",\n        \"Specify phosphate-enhanced conditions for the DHAP-de